<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tajik President Signs Accord with Rebel Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, May 18 (Xinhua) - Tajikistan's President Emomali
Rakhmonov today legalized major Islamist opposition parties and
removed the major obstacle for national reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
The president signed a draft political agreement and memorandum
with the opposition leader Said Abdullah Nuri in Bishkek, capital
of neighboring Kyrgyzstan.
</P>
<P>
According to Interfax News Agency reports, both sides will ratify
the mutual understanding agreement and the law of amnesty.
</P>
<P>
The president agreed to re-shuffle the cabinet and absorb the
opposition representatives. The government will also lift the ban
on opposition activities after their armed forces being disarmed
and redesignated.
</P>
<P>
The disagreement of the two parties on those issues had blocked
the peace negotiation in last April.
</P>
<P>
The Memorandum of Bishkek said the peace talks have paved the
way for constructive development of political situation in
tajikistan.
</P>
<P>
The leaders of both parties are satisfied with the outcome of
the negotiation. Rakhmonov said after the talks that a breakthrough
has emerged in the process of national reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
The latest round of peace talks were held in Bishkek, the
capital of Kyrgyzstan, over the past three days. It was the
fourth meeting between the two leaders, the earlier meetings
were held in Russia, Afghanistan and Iran.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
