<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Labor MP Denies Bribery Allegation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 18 (Xinhua) -- One of Britain's ruling Labor
Party's newly-elected members of parliament (MP), Mohammed Sarwar,
said Sunday claims that he bribed a rival election candidate are
"totally false".
</P>
<P>
The claims were made in the News of the World newspaper, which
said that Sarwar, the 46-year-old multi-millionaire Labor MP for
Glasgow Govan, paid 5,000 pounds (8,000 U.S. dollars) to an
Independent Labor candidate not to try hard to win votes.
</P>
<P>
The Glasgow Govan MP, also Britain's first Muslim MP, said that
he would be consulting his lawyers about a possible action for
defamation.
</P>
<P>
Labor officials reacted to the first potentially serious blow
to Prime Minister Blair's administration by ordering an immediate
investigation, warning that Sarwar would face tough action if he
was found to have done anything improper.
</P>
<P>
A senior Labor spokesman said Saturday night that they would
question Sarwar about the allegations.
</P>
<P>
"It is not appropriate to comment until we have heard Mr
Sarwar's side of the story. Should further action be needed in the
light of this, we will not hesitate to take it."
</P>
<P>
If true, the allegations will embarrass the Labor Party, which
won a landslide victory in the May 1 general election and had
promised to change from a Conservative administration riddled with
allegations of financial and sexual impropriety. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
