<BODY>
<HEADLINE> People's Daily Publishes Editorial On Land Protection (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 18 (Xinhua) -- The Beijing-based People's Daily
today published an editorial entitled "Protection of Farmland
Brooks No Delay", urging the whole nation to pay more attention to
the protection of arable lands.
</P>
<P>
Applauding the notice issued by the State Council today further
enhancing land management and the protection of arable lands, the
Editorial said protecting arable lands across the country has
become an urgent need, and some strategic measures should be
immediately taken.
</P>
<P>
Due to the efforts made by the Chinese Communist Party Central
Committee and the State Council, the trend of chaotic land
occupation and land abuse has been controlled in recent years.
But, the editorial noted, the whole nation must remain highly
vigilant about the land situation because the problems are still
very serious.
</P>
<P>
"The average arable land area per capita in China is less than
half of the world's average. And most of China's arable lands are
located in mountain, hilly, plateau, arid or semi-arid areas, and
many of them are suffering from soil erosion and deterioration,"
the editorial says.
</P>
<P>
It also said that the adjustment in agricultural structures and
natural disasters would lead to a loss of some arable land, and
that economic development in China will change many arable lands
into some contruction projects, and the even larger population in
the future will require still more arable lands for food
production.
</P>
<P>
"If correct and effective measures are not adopted now, the
balance between the arable lands' feeding capacity and human
necessity would be destroyed," the editorial said, "so protecting
the arable land is the protection of our own lifeline."
</P>
<P>
In some places, illegal land transactions still exist, and
outside funds are still being attracted at the price of lost
arable lands, the editorial said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
