<DOCNO> XIE19970519.0008 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> People's Daily Publishes Editorial on Land Protection (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The editorial noted that leaders of the central authorities
recently pointed out that China should adopt the toughest measures
in the world to manage land and protect arable land.
</P>
<P>
"Concerning our country's specific conditions and the current
situation -- if the misuse of arable land doesn't come to a halt
despite repeated efforts by the central government to ban it,
there are no other options for us," it said.
</P>
<P>
It went on to say that the reason why the problem of the loss
of arable land couldn't find a fundamental solution over a long
period of time lies in the incompleteness of China's system for
land management, as well as in the country's legal system.
</P>
<P>
"We need to carry out a scheme of comprehensive management,
which covers all relevant aspects, to solve the land problem," it
suggested.
</P>
<P>
Starting from October 1 this year, the article noted,
activities of sabotaging land resources would receive criminal
penalties in accordance with the amended Criminal Law.
</P>
<P>
"This signifies another major progress our country has made in
completing the legal system for land management," it commented.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the editorial noted, analyses by relevant departments
showed that in the coming 10 to 15 years, by means of intensifying
land management, tapping potentials and promoting the intensive
use of land, the area of arable land could be effectively
increased, while land for construction could also be guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
"Therefore, it is absolutely possible to reach the strategic
goal set by President Jiang Zemin that the overall area of arable
land should be guaranteed an increase, and should by no means
suffer a decrease," it asserted.
</P>
<P>
It added that rearrangement of the land has also been proved to
be a successful way to increase arable land, citing east China's
Jiangsu Province as an example.
</P>
<P>
The province is planning to merge its more than 280,000 natural
villages into over 50,000 villages of larger sizes, which can
produce approximately three million mu (200,000 hectares) of new
arable land.
</P>
<P>
The editorial cited it as the responsibility of every Chinese
citizen to protect the country's arable land, and a social
atmosphere of using the land economically and cherishing the
arable land should be created by enhancing the land awareness
among the entire people, especially the leading officials.
</P>
<P>
"We are obliged to carefully protect and develop the land which
our ancestors have cultivated for 5,000 years, and pass it on to
our future generations," the editorial said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
