<HEADLINE> Mbeki Leaves for Zaire for Talks With Kabila </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 18 (Xinhua) -- South African Deputy
President Thabo Mbeki left Pretoria for Zaire this afternoon for
talks with Laurent Kabila, who declared himself the Head of State
of "the Democratic Republic of Congo" on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki, who has been deeply involved in seeking a peaceful
settlement to the Zaire crisis, was accompanied by Defense
Minister Joe Modise, Deputy Foreign Affairs Minister Aziz Pahad
during his last-ditch diplomatic efforts to win support for a
South African plan to bring democracy to the central African
nation, said an informed source here.
</P>
<P>
The talks between Mbeki and Kabila are scheduled to take place
tonight at Kabila's stronghold Lubumbashi, the second largest
city of Zaire, said the source.
</P>
<P>
When asked whether South Africa would recognize Kabila's
government, Foreign Affairs Minister Alfred Nzo, who was at
Waterkloof Airport near Pretoria to see the delegation off, said
that "the people of Zaire will decide, but there is no reason why
we would not support him."
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, President Nelson Mandela declined to comment on
developments in Zaire and Kabila's unilateral assumption of
power.
</P>
<P>
The president will make an announcement once Mbeki returns
from talks with Kabila in Lubumbashi, said Mandela's spokesman
Parks Mankahlana. 
</P>
</TEXT>
