<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Calm Returns to Kinshasa After Looting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(by Guo Ming)
</P>
<P>
BRAZZAVILLE, May 18 (Xinhua) -- Calm returned to Kinshasa today as
Zaire's self-proclaimed Head of State Laurent Kabila sent more troops
to gain full control of the capital after overnight looting by
the defeated government soldiers.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, state television and radio said Kabila's men
earlier today captured the military camp of the special division
loyal to Mobutu Sese Seko, the last stronghold of Mobutu's
government forces.
</P>
<P>
"The Alliance of Democratic Forces for the Liberation of
Congo-Zaire has gained full control of the situation in
Kinshasa," said an announcement carried by the state radio which
has already been in the hands of Kabila's troops.
</P>
<P>
An overnight heavy fighting happened in the southwestern part
of the capital where the military camp is located, but Kabila's
troops finally gained an upper hand.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, Kabila sent the second dispatch of supporting
troops to Kinshasa to boost his control of the capital.
</P>
<P>
The tv and radio repeatedly broadcasted an order from Kabila,
saying that any forms of crime including looting are strictly
forbidden, and looters would be severely punished.
</P>
<P>
Kabila also called on local residents in Kinshasa to remain
calm and carry on their normal business.
</P>
<P>
Many disgruntled civilians who have long suffered from
poverty, especially the frustrated young people, also took part
in Saturday's looting in downtown Kinshasa. Many shops, hotels,
and houses of the rich people suffered from the robbery.
</P>
<P>
But peace returned to the capital, teemed with a population of
five million, as local residents began to appear in the streets
and clean the looted places in the city.
</P>
<P>
Kabila, who has declared to change the country's name from Zaire
to the Democratic Republic of Congo, is scheduled to announce the
name list of his new cabinet by Monday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Zaire and neighboring Congo's state radios both
reported that Mobutu had late last night arrived in Morocco for a
temporary stay. But the final destination of his exile trip can
not be acertained. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
