<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain to Launch War on Drugs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 18 (Xinhua) -- Britain's new Labor government will
launch a war on drugs as a new Home Office research shows that one
in five people arrested by police in Britain is on heroin.
</P>
<P>
A study of those arrested in four British cities, London,
Manchester, Notingham and Cambridge, over a 21-month period
reveals that 360,000 of the 1.8 million arrests the police
annually make are regular heroin users.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Prime Minister Tony Blair will Monday
announce a new cabinet task force, a ministerial committee, to
coordinate the war on drugs. The committee will appoint a
high-profile team to lead the fight against drug abuse and the
illegal drugs trade.
</P>
<P>
Under new measures, to be introduced on a pilot basis, an
initial drug test would be carried out on any offender suspected
of being a drug user prior to sentencing.
</P>
<P>
It tested positive, he or she would be forced to accept
treatment and be subject to random tests throughout the
three-month order.
</P>
<P>
According to government statistics, the number of people
convicted of drug-related offenses has more than trebled over the
last decade to 93,000 last year. The number of drugs seizures has
risen four-fold to 115,000 annually. The number of notified
addicts has doubled since 1986 to 37,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
