<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-18 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PNA Official: More Arab Coordination Needed to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, May 18 (Xinhua) -- A top Palestinian official said here
today that more Arab coordination is needed to salvage the
deadlocked Middle East peace process, Radio Jordan reported.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Local government of the Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) Saeb Erekat made the remarks while conveying a
message from PNA President Yasser Arafat to Jordanian Prime
Minister Abdul Salam Majali a message and asked him to hand it to
King Hussein. The message is said to be focused on the bilateral
relations and the latest development of the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Arab coordination looks ever more important as the Israeli
government's settlement policy and unilateral measures have led to
the latest mission of U.S. special envoy Dennis Ross to failure,
said Erekat who is on his second visit here within two months.
</P>
<P>
Arafat has refused to meet Ross again and written a letter to
U.S. President Bill Clinton calling for his personal efforts to
reactivate the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Majali responded to Erekat's remarks by saying that the
Palestinian-Israeli dialogue is the best way to break the
stalement and Jordan will firmly support the Palestinians to
achieve their rights on their national soil.
</P>
<P>
Erekat, chief Palestinian negotiator with Israel, also told
Majali that the latest Palestinian-Israeli meeting and the talks
with Ross were centered on Jerusalem and Israeli troop
redeployment in some West Bank areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
