<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1500 GMT May 19 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS -- Greek Foreign Minister Theodoros Pangalos left for
Israel Monday on a two-day official visit. He will hold talks with
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and his Israeli
counterpart David Levy on bilateral ties, especially in the
economic and military sectors.
</P>
<P>
SEOUL -- Veteran opposition leader Kim Dae Jung was elected
Monday as his party's presidential nominee to run for the national
vote in December. Kim said that he was willing to discuss with the
second largest opposition party, the United Liberal Democrats,
about putting up a single opposition candidate against the ruling
New Korea Party.
</P>
<P>
ISLAMABAD -- The Iranian government welcomed Pakistani Prime
Minister Nawaz Sharif's proposal for holding a 5-Nation
Conference to bring Afghan warring factions together for a
permanent peace in war-torn Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The five nations are Pakistan, Iran, Uzbekistan, Turkmenistan
and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
HARARE -- South African President Nelson Mandela arrived here
Monday for a three-day state visit, his first, to Zimbabwe and was
expected to hold talks with Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe
later the day.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Jordan's Crown Prince Hassan left here Monday on a
2-day working visit to Italy to further bilateral relations under
the framework of a Euro-Jordanian partnership in the security,
economy and culture.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak left here Monday for
Germany to promote bilateral ties and seek Bonn's counsel on
breaking the Mideast peace deadlock, the Egyptian Middle East News
Agency (MENA) reported.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak, accompanied by a high-powered delegation including
Foreign Minister Amr Moussa, is expected to meet German President
Roman Herzog and Chancellor Helmut Kohl on means of rejuvenating
the peace march.
</P>
<P>
SINGAPORE -- Singapore and Australia began a week-long joint
naval exercise here Monday, announced the Defense Ministry.
</P>
<P>
MANILA -- The 30th International General Meeting of the Pacific
Basin Economic Council (PBEC), which formally opened here Monday,
has expressed its full confidence in the future of Hongkong.
</P>
<P>
In a resolution adopted by its Steering Committee and Board of
Directors Sunday, the PBEC said that it recognizes China's
forthcoming resumption of its exercise of sovereignty over
Hongkong. 
</P>
