<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain to Ban Tobacco Sports Sponsorship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 19 (Xinhua) -- Britain's new Labor government said
today that it would outlaw the sponsorship of sports events by
tobacco companies.
</P>
<P>
Health Secretary Frank Dobson confirmed that the commitment to
end tobacco advertising announced in the Queen's Speech last week
would include a ban on sponsorship.
</P>
<P>
Dobson said in a speech to the Royal College of Nursing's
congress in Yorkshire that sports would be given time to find
other sponsors.
</P>
<P>
"We recognize that some sports are heavily dependent on tobacco
sponsorship. We will therefore give them time and help to reduce
their dependency on tobacco and replace it with sponsorship from
more benign sources," he added.
</P>
<P>
The decision was welcomed by anti-smoking campaigners, but
tobacco companies, while disappointed by the move, said that a
variety of sports would suffer financially as a result of the ban,
but they did not think it would have any effect on the consumption
of tobacco products.
</P>
<P>
They argued that a ban on advertising would not cut cigarette
consumption as the ads only persuaded existing smokers to change
brands.
</P>
<P>
Cigarette companies spend millions sponsoring sports such as
cricket, golf, darts, Rugby and Formula One motor racing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970519.0023 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Works Out Plan for Development of Scientific Research </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 19 (Xinhua) -- China plans to build up four
nationwide networks for scientific research, instrument supply,
maintenance of instruments, analysis and testing, and information
in Beijing, Shanghai, and other cities where scientists and
researchers are concentrated.
</P>
<P>
According to China's development plan of scientific research
conditions for the Ninth Five-Year Plan period (1996-2000) and
long-range objectives for 2010 issued today, China will form a
relatively comprehensive service network for Chinese scientists.
</P>
<P>
The scientific research conditions mainly cover instruments for
scientific research, lab animals, chemical reagents, books, and
data that provide the necessary support for launching scientific
research.
</P>
<P>
According to the plan drawn up by the State Science and
Technology Commission (SSTC), China is to utilize advantages of
high-tech development zones in Beijing, Shanghai, and Changchun
for building bases for producing self-developed patented
instruments.
</P>
<P>
China plans to raise its market share of Chinese-patented
instruments from 13 percent in 1995 to 26 percent by the end of
2000.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, China will introduce foreign technology or
establish joint ventures for producing medium and high-grade
instruments for research in biology, biochemistry, new materials,
and mineral resources.
</P>
<P>
An official with the SSTC said that Beijing will lead in
sharing the use of large instruments that have a low utilization
ratio. The SSTC, the State Education Commission, and some other
departments have collected 13 million yuan (1.6 million US
dollars) for establishing a fund to pay the operation charges of
those instruments.
</P>
<P>
The plan stipulates that China will spread the use of
clean-level lab animals by 2000 and SPS-level animals (animals not
carrying specified causative agents) by 2010.
</P>
<P>
China is to improve its chemical reagent production and supply
networks in the coming years.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1995, China's scientific research institutions
and universities had bought instruments valued at 28 billion yuan
(nearly 3.5 billion dollars) and produced more than 6,000 kinds of
reagents.
</P>
<P>
China has an annual lab animal breeding capacity of 13 million
and established more than 10,000 libraries, archives, and
information centers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
