<HEADLINE> Angolan Club Beats Ivorian Champions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 19 (Xinhua) -- Primeiro Agosto went on a
five-goal rampage in Angola this weekend to destroy Ivorians
Africa Sports National in a Champions League second-round clash.
</P>
<P>
The result proved the biggest shock of the eight ties and the
Luanda club will join the champions of Algeria, Egypt, Ghana,
Morocco, Mozambique, South Africa and Tunisia in the group phase.
</P>
<P>
Primeiro had won only two of seven previous home games spanning
17 years, never scored more than three goals in front of their
supporters, and failed to progress beyond the second round.
</P>
<P>
After battling to overcome modest Notwane of Botswana in the
first round, Primeiro snatched a last-minute equaliser in the
Ivory Coast against a team packed with international stars.
</P>
<P>
It was an opportune time for the Angolans to make an impact as
prize money is on offer for the first time in the leading
continental club event with each quarter-finalist receiving
150,000 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The survivors will be divided into two mini-leagues starting on
August 22 with matches staged on a home-and-away basis and the
group winners qualifying for a two-leg final.
</P>
<P>
There was another upset in Mozambique where Ferroviario
trounced Unisport Bafang from Cameroon 4-0 with Jorge Vulande
scoring twice and Arnaldo Ouana and Tomas Inguane once.
</P>
<P>
Veteran midfielder Ahmed al-Kass struck after eight minutes in
Zambia to give defending champions Zamalek from Egypt a 1-0 win
over Mufulira Wanderers.
</P>
<P>
Although the Cairo club have lifted the trophy a record four
times, their away record is poor with this success being the first
in 13 matches covering five years.
</P>
<P>
Tunisian outfit Club Africain equalled the record overall
winning margin after flying to the Indian Ocean island of Reunion
and giving Saint-Pierroise another five-goal hiding. 
</P>
</TEXT>
