<BODY>
<HEADLINE> If Ignored, Russia Would Review NATO Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, May 19 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
today assured parliamentary leaders that Russia will review its
relations with NATO if the alliance ignores the opinions of Moscow.
</P>
<P>
If the North Atlantic Treaty Organization decides to takes
in former Soviet republics as new members, Russia will reconsider
its relations with NATO, Yeltsin was quoted by the Itar-Tass news
agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin met with speakers and party chiefs of both houses of
parliament today, mainly to explain the new deal agreed with NATO,
which is poised to expand eastward to take in former Soviet allies
in Eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
The president said the treaty to be signed next week in Paris
should be seen "not as a compromise but as a balanced result,
corresponding to our interests and the interests of the alliance,"
Itar-Tass said.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin, who is apparently trying to overcome criticisms of the
accord with NATO from the opposition, said Russia didn't make any
concessions on issues of principle in the six rounds of
negotiations with NATO.
</P>
<P>
He explained that Russia had to seek to minimize the
consequences of the expanded NATO when its eastward enlargement
became unpreventable.
</P>
<P>
One year ago, NATO said Russia didn't have the right to protest
against NATO expansion. But now, for both sides, the central issue
had become how to find a way to avoid confrontation, the president
said.
</P>
<P>
He said the document was conducive to solving the question of
European security on the basis of equality.
</P>
<P>
He said Russia had won important assurances from the West,
including a pledge not to move nuclear weapons or other forces
into new member states in Eastern Europe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
