<HEADLINE> Iran Asks Iraq to Clarify Fate of Iranian POWs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, May 19 (Xinhua) -- Iran today called on international
organizations to put pressure on the Iraqi government to clarify
the status Iranian prisoners of war in Iraq, the Persian Daily
Iran reported today.
</P>
<P>
Mohammad Balar, spokesman for the commission in charge of
Iranian Prisoners of War (POW), said that the Iraqi government
should give an explicit response to Iran's request on the fate of
that group of Iranians.
</P>
<P>
About 20,000 "Iranians have disappeared and captured by the
Iraqi regime during the eight-year war between Iran and Iraq from
1980 to 1988," he was quoted by the Persian Daily Iran.
</P>
<P>
He added that the Iranian government in a move to show its good
will has released about 1,000 Iraqi POWs in two stages
unilaterally.
</P>
<P>
But, the Iraqi government has not reciprocated Iran's measure,
he added.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also criticized the Iraqi government, especially
the Iraqi Foreign Minister Mohammed Saeed al-Sahhaf, for not
abiding by their promises.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, Al-Sahhaf in a meeting with his
Iranian counterpart Ali Akbar Velayati in Rabat, Morocco, in
March, had promised to take practical steps for the settlement of
the issue.
</P>
<P>
Iran and Iraq fought a bloody war from 1980 to 1988. Iranian
Majlis (Parliament) Speaker Ali Akbar Nateq-Nouri said earlier
that the damages inflicted by the eight-year Iraqi imposed war on
Iran totals 1,000 billion U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
