<HEADLINE> Beijing-Kowloon Railway Well Protected </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANCHANG, May 19 (Xinhua) -- China's longest railway, the
newly-built Beijing-Kowloon Railway, is well maintained by cities
and towns along the railway line.
</P>
<P>
Chen Jiping, office director of the Central Commission for
Comprehensive Management of Public Security, said here today that
all nine provinces and municipalities along the Beijing-Kowloon
Railway have made every effort to keep the transportation artery
safe and clear of obstructions.
</P>
<P>
"Apart from its significance as an artery linking Hong Kong and
Beijing and other interior areas of the motherland, the railway
has also been regarded as a lifeline for regions along it to
develop their local economies," he explained.
</P>
<P>
In Jiangxi Province, the Provincial Department of Public
Security and the local railway administration have jointly
launched a campaign to increase public awareness about protecting
the trunk line, which covered all the towns, villages, schools,
factories and mines along the railway. To date, 170,000 people
have been involved in this campaign.
</P>
<P>
During the past one and a half months, Anhui Province has
checked 20 bridges and 179 culverts on the railway within its
border, to remove any possible threat to a safe journey on the
line.
</P>
<P>
According to Chen, many places along the railway have also
introduced a responsibility system, which requires major
government officials to be fully responsible for the safety and
smooth operation of the line. 
</P>
</TEXT>
