<HEADLINE> Long Jail Terms Demanded For Hanbo Suspects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, May 19 (Xinhua) -- Winding up a four-month trial
resulting from the big Hanbo money-for-power scandal, South Korean
prosecutors today asked for long jail terms for 11 businessmen,
politicians and bankers charged with bribery, sleaze and
embezzlement.
</P>
<P>
Prosecutors demanded 20-years imprisonment for Chung Tae-soo,
founder of the Hanbo Group, charged with embezzling 191.1 billion
won (214.7 million U.S. dollars) from the company's account.
</P>
<P>
He was also accused of offering 3.25 billion won (3.65 million
dollars) in bribes to senior politicians and bank officials, in
collaboration with his son and a former company executive, in
return for mammoth loans.
</P>
<P>
The bankruptcy in January of the Hanbo Steel Company, the
flagship of the Hanbo Group, triggered a chain collapse of
business associates and led to the biggest yet corruption
investigation in the country.
</P>
<P>
Prosecutors asked for six years imprisonment for Chung's son,
Chung Bo-keun, the present chairman of the Hanbo Group, for
alleged bribery and embezzlement. The group ranks 14th among the
nation's conglomerates.
</P>
<P>
Prosecutor Park San-gil said the Hanbo scandal was "a large
scale corruption case perpetrated in collaboration by immoral
politicians, bankers and corporate executives."
</P>
<P>
"It has even damaged the nation's reputation," he said.
</P>
<P>
Prosecutors also asked for five to eight year jail terms for
another nine people allegedly involved in the scandal, including a
former home affairs minister, four lawmakers and three bank chiefs.
</P>
<P>
In a latest move by the prosecution which had vowed to expose
the largest corruption scandal in the country, Kim Hyun-chul, the
second son of President Kim Young-sam, and Kim Ki-sup, former
deputy chief of the National Security Planning Agency, were
arrested for allegedly taking kickbacks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
