<HEADLINE> HK PLC Solicits Public Views on Three Draft Bills </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 19 (Xinhua) -- The Provisional Legislative
Council (PLC) of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR)
today invited members of the public and interested groups to air
their views on three draft bills on provisional district
organizations.
</P>
<P>
The bills, the Urban Council (Amendment) Bill 1997, the
Regional Council (Amendment) Bill 1997 and the District Board
(Amendment) Bill 1997, were tabled to the PLC last Saturday for
first and second readings.
</P>
<P>
As the terms of the existing Urban Council, Regional Council
and District Boards expire on June 30, 1997, it is necessary to
fill the resultant vacuum by setting up provisional district
organizations, namely, the Provisional Urban Council, the
Provisional Regional Council and 18 Provisional District Boards,
on July 1 along with the establishment of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (HKSAR), a PLC spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The provisions of the bills include:
</P>
<P>
-- All members of the provisional district organizations shall
be appointed by the Chief Executive of the HKSAR;
</P>
<P>
-- The terms of office of members of these provisional district
organizations shall commence on July 1, 1997 and expire on a date
not later than December 31, 1999; and
</P>
<P>
-- The Provisional Urban Council and the Provisional Regional
Council both consist of not more than 50 members, a 25 percent
increase over the two existing councils. The membership of each
one of 18 Provisional District Councils shall be extended by 25
percent to not more than 40.
</P>
<P>
A Bills Committee, chaired by PLC member Chan Kam-lam, has been
formed to study the three bills.
</P>
<P>
Members of the public and interested parties can send written
submissions to PLC Secretariat in Shenzhen, south China, or to the
Secretariat's homepage on the Internet by Thursday. They can also
ask to meet with the Bills Committee to give their comments
face-to-face, the spokesman said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
