<HEADLINE> Children's Village in Tianjin Benefits Orphans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, May 19 (Xinhua) -- The Tianjin SOS Children's Village
has provided adequate living conditions for the healthy growth of
228 orphans, since it was founded a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
Being the first of its kind in China, the village has set up a
good model for the other Chinese children's villages, said Helmut
Kutin, chairman of the International SOS Children's Villages,
after he visited the village.
</P>
<P>
More than 190 orphans, from Tianjin City, Hebei, Shanxi, and
Shaanxi provinces, are now living in the Tianjin SOS Children's
Village, which covers a floor space of over 6,600 sq. meters. It
has 18 "families" and an apartment building for orphans.
</P>
<P>
The International SOS Children's Villages, an international
non-governmental charity organization, has opened more than 300
villages in about 100 countries.
</P>
<P>
All the children adopted by those villages will live in
"families", which have unmarried (or divorced) women as "mothers".
</P>
<P>
"Our village pays great attention to the family atmosphere and
children's education," said Wang Zhenlin, the village chief,
adding, "the mothers are also teachers and friends of the
children, who are apt to find and develop children's talents."
</P>
<P>
More than 40 orphans, adopted by the village, have grown into
adults, 37 have found jobs and four have entered college.
</P>
<P>
The charity has opened children's villages in other Chinese
cities, including Yantai, Qiqihar, Nanchang, Chengdu, Kaifeng,
Putian, and is planning to build such villages in Xinjiang Uygur
Autonomous Region and Tibet Autonomous Region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
