<DOCNO> XIE19970519.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Economy Grows Moderately in April </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 19 (Xinhua) -- The national economic development
in China continued to grow moderately in April, Ye Zhen, spokesman
for the State Statistical Bureau (SSB), said here today.
</P>
<P>
All state economic indicators showed a moderate increase, Ye
said at a news conference held today, which was attended by Liu
Hong, newly-appointed SSB director.
</P>
<P>
The domestic industrial output value maintained a stable growth in
April. The industrial added-value generated by enterprises at or
above the township level totalled 174.3 billion yuan last month,
11.9 percent up from the last year's same period, Ye said.
</P>
<P>
The added-value secured by light industrial manufacturers rose
to 76.4 billion yuan while that of heavy industrial makers climbed
to 97.9 billion yuan, with each registering an 11.9 percent rise.
</P>
<P>
The sales rate of industrial goods came to 95.21 percent, 0.49
percent higher than the same month of last year.
</P>
<P>
In the first four months of this year, Ye said, the country's
investment in fixed assets was 242.5 billion yuan, representing a
15 percent increase. The growth range was 1.1 percent higher than
the average rate of the previous three months.
</P>
<P>
The retail sales of consumer goods rose 13.6 percent at 210.1
billion yuan, registering a 12.4 percent real growth after
allowing for the price rise.
</P>
<P>
The volume of retail sales of consumer goods in urban districts
totalled 128.7 billion yuan while that in rural areas accounted to
81.3 billion yuan, increasing by 13.4 percent and 10.8 percent
respectively.
</P>
<P>
The national import and export value in April soared to 26
billion US dollars, a 16.7 percent increase compared with last
year's same period.
</P>
<P>
The imports increased 2.9 percent for the first time since the
beginning of the year as a result of more imports by the
processing trade, Ye said.
</P>
<P>
The growth of prices further slowed down in April, with the
retail price of consumer goods rising 1.1 percent from the same
month a year ago.
</P>
<P>
Residents consumer prices increased by 3.2 percent last month,
0.8 percent lower than that in March.
</P>
<P>
The national economic operation is on the right track. Key
tasks in macro-economic control for the coming months are to
prevent financial risks, tighten the control over newly-built
projects, deepen the reforms at the state-owned enterprises, and
speed up changes in the economic growth mode, Ye said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970519.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi PM Postpones State Visit Due to Storm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Dhaka, May 19 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi Prime Minister Sheikh
Hasina has postponed her scheduled state visit to Spain and
directed all necessary arrangements to be made for protecting
lives and property from the devastating cyclonic storm, said an
official press release.
</P>
<P>
No report of casualties was received till now.
</P>
<P>
From late this afternoon, the cyclonic storm started sweeping
Bangladesh's biggest port city Chittagong and the adjoining areas
at a speed of 160 to 170 kilometers per hour, said Met Office
sources.
</P>
<P>
District control room said that the storm started hitting
almost all the coastal areas with light rainfall accompanied by
gusty wind. However, no tidal surge was reported.
</P>
<P>
A number of electricity posts and trees were uprooted in the
Chittagong city causing disruption of power while the
communication between tourist city Cox's Bazar and Chittagong was
suspended this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina has directed to open Control Room
at her office to monitor the situation of cyclonic storm round the
clock. She also visited Monitoring Cell at the Relief and Disaster
Ministry this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
She expressed her confidence that the people would face the
catastrophe of the cyclone with utmost coverage and fortitude.
There would be no dearth of relief and succor to ameliorate the
sufferings of the affected people, she added.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said the government has adequate stock of
relief materials and preparations to face any eventuality. She
pointed out that about 1,000 medical teams have kept stand by to
face the situation.
</P>
<P>
According to reports received here today, volunteers and local
administration have transferred more than 300,000 coastal dwellers
to different cyclone shelters.
</P>
<P>
Maritime ports of Chittagong and Cox's Bazar have been advised
to keep hoisted great danger signal No. 10.
</P>
<P>
All fishing boats and trawlers over north Bay of Bengal have
been advised to remain in shelter till further notice.
</P>
<P>
Besides, members of police, Coast Guard and Civil Defense have
been instructed to extend all sorts of cooperation and assistance
to the local bodies in facing the cyclone.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
