<HEADLINE> Localization of Civil Service Urged in Macao </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, May 19 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese official has urged the
Portuguese side to take effective measures to step up the process
of the localization of the civil service in Macao.
</P>
<P>
Wang Xi'an, representative of the Chinese side of the Three
Leading Issues Working Panel on the Sino-Portuguese Joint Liaison
Group (JLG), said here today after a meeting with his Portuguese
counterparts that the Chinese side had paid special attention to
the localization of civil service.
</P>
<P>
"The problem with the localization of civil service is that the
 number of Chinese-speaking civil servants posted in middle and
senior positions is so small that it is in sharp contrast to the
fact that the Chinese population constitutes the dominant part of
local residents," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We hope the Portuguese side will have greater sense of
responsibility and urgency in resolving the issue," said Wang.
</P>
<P>
The working panel's closed-door meeting today on the three
leading issues -- localization of civil service, localization of
law and the use of Chinese as an official language -- is in
preparation for the upcoming 29th plenary session of the JLG in
June in Lisbon.
</P>
<P>
At today's meeting, the Portuguese side briefed the Chinese
side on the progress in the three leading issues of Macao's
transition. And the Chinese side responded that certain progress
was scored but that was not enough, considering that only two and
half years are left before the handover of power in December 1999.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese side concludes that if the three leading issues,
especially the localization of civil service, cannot be addressed
in time and properly, the smooth handover of power and the stable
transition will be affected," Wang said.
</P>
<P>
"Although the Portuguese side has made some efforts, it is far
from satisfactory with the localization of civil service," added
Wang.
</P>
<P>
In addition, he said that greater efforts are needed in the
localization of law and the use of Chinese as an official
language, although there is progress.
</P>
<P>
A large number of laws are yet to be translated and localized,
and Portuguese is still the dominant language in some government
departments, and some government documents only have Portuguese
version without a Chinese version, Wang said.
</P>
<P>
Jorge Mendes, Wang's Portuguese counterpart, said that the
Macao government is making efforts in the translation of law, and
has stepped up the training of more professionals in law and civil
 service.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970519.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-19 </DATE_TIME>
