<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 19 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Jordan's exports of industrial products amounted to
about 516 million U.S. dollars in the first half of 1996, as
compared to some 476 million dollars during the same period in
1995, said Amman Chamber of Industry Chairman Khaldou Abu Haasan
on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Industry, traditionally a weak sector in the country's economy,
now employs about 0.03 percent of the total population of the
country but accounts for 19 percent of the gross national product
(GDP) in 1995.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Saudi Arabia's Prince and billionaire Al Walid Ben
Talal announced Sunday his participation in the Jordan Magnesia
Company, which will extract minerals from the Dead Sea with a
capital of 43 million dollars, Jordan Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
Prince Al Walid signed a new agreement whereby he becomes a
founder shareholder in the company, said the prince's office in a
press release.
</P>
<P>
Saudi is one of Jordan's most important trade partners within
the Arab World.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt's state-owned Company for Construction and
Housing this week offered investors 10 percent in its General
Upper Egypt Contracting Company (GUECC) at a minimum price of 35
Egyptian pounds (10 U.S. dollars) per share.
</P>
<P>
The firm said the public offer of at least 30,000 shares, of
the firm's total 300,000 shares, would begin from May 20 to 22.
</P>
<P>
The holding company is also offering 30,000 shares to its
employees.
</P>
<P>
Individuals must apply for at least 50 shares while mutual
funds and financial firms should have a 1,000-share minimum.
</P>
<P>
The share offer is part of Egypt's privatization-led economic
reform program.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian Minister of Economy and International Trade
Nawal el-Tatawi will inaugurate the African Insurance Conference,
due to be held here on May 24-29.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian Sharque Company for Insurance will host the 6-day
conference, with the participation of around 500 experts from the
region.
</P>
<P>
The conference will discuss means of developing the insurance
market in the light of recent changes witnessed by the continent
and of boosting cooperation among African insurance agencies.
</P>
