<HEADLINE> Veteran Opposition Leader Elected Presidential Nominee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, May 19 (Xinhua) -- Veteran opposition leader Kim Dae
Jung was elected today as his party's presidential nominee to run
for the national vote in December.
</P>
<P>
Kim defeated his sole challenger, Chung Dai-chul, in his
National Congress for New Politics party, by a landslide victory
of 3,224 votes against 907.
</P>
<P>
To consolidate the opposition, Kim said after the nomination
that he was willing to discuss with the second largest opposition
party, the United Liberal Democrats, the possibility of putting up
a single opposition candidate against the ruling New Korea Party.
</P>
<P>
President Kim Young-sam's New Korea Party is suffering from a
string of corruption scandals.
</P>
<P>
Kim's son, Kim Hyun-chul was arrested Saturday on corruption
charges linked with the bribery scandal surrounding the Hanbo
steel group which collapsed in January.
</P>
<P>
Kim Dae Jung, 72, was forced into exile in the 1970s and was
sentenced to death in 1980 by the regime of former president Chun
Doo Hwan. The death sentence was suspended the following year and
commuted to 20 years in prison in 1982 before he was sent to the
United States.
</P>
<P>
Kim is making his fourth presidential bid after his attempts in
1971, 1987 and 1992 were foiled. 
</P>
</TEXT>
