<HEADLINE> Britain to Assist UN on Cyprus Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, May 19 (Xinhua) -- Britain's special envoy for
Cyprus, Sir David Hannay, is to visit the island in early June to
assist the United Nations in solving the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
This was announced here today by Britain's High Commissioner
in Nicosia David Madden after a 45-minute meeting with Cypriot
President Glafcos Clerides at Presidential Palace.
</P>
<P>
Madden pledged that the British government would do its very
best to assist U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan in what he plans
to do on the issue.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan has announced his
intention to invite President Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader
Rauf Denktash to have direct talks on Cyprus issue in New York in
the second half of June.
</P>
<P>
Madden said he hoped to announce soon an early meeting between
Cypriot Foreign Minister Ioannis Kasoulides and British Foreign
Secretary Robin Cook.
</P>
<P>
Asked to comment on reservations expressed by the Cypriot
government that there was no enough preparation for direct
negotiations, Madden noted that U.N. preparatory efforts are
continuing.
</P>
<P>
"It's obvious that we still have a bit of time," he added.
</P>
<P>
Referring to a reference made to Cyprus by Queen Elizabeth II,
in her speech delivered at the official opening of the British
Parliament on May 14, Madden said that "there was a commitment in
the Queen's speech, that the British government would continue to
work for progress and indeed toward a settlement of the Cyprus
problem."
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus problem has remained unsolved since 1974 when the
island was divided after Turkish troops occupied its northern
third in the wake of an Athens-backed coup. 
</P>
</TEXT>
