<TEXT>
<P>
ZHUHAI, May 19 (Xinhua) -- Police chiefs from the Guangdong
Province and neighboring Macao met today in this southern coastal
city to discuss how to enhance anti-crime cooperation.
</P>
<P>
According to Zhu Mingjian, vice director of the Guangdong
Provincial Department of Public Security, senior police officers
from the two sides mainly discussed joint efforts to crack down on
organized crimes, trans-border crimes, illegal immigration,
forgery of documents, and smuggling.
</P>
<P>
The Guangdong police also expressed great concern about the
public security situation in Macao, recently plagued by a series
of crimes.
</P>
<P>
Police officers from Guangdong committed themselves to full
support of the Macao police's crime crackdown, and pledged to
spare no efforts to hunt and extradite any criminal offender
escaping into the inland areas.
</P>
<P>
"Guangdong shall by no means become a haven for mafia crimes
from Hong Kong or Macao" they said.
</P>
<P>
Zhu Mingjian, vice director of the Guangdong Provincial
Department of Public Security, assured his counterpart in Macao
that his department will provide whatever support needed by the
Macao police.
</P>
<P>
The two sides worked out some concrete measures, which include
setting up hotlines for cracking down on mafia and drugs,
increasing information exchanges, and strengthening cooperation in
police training. 
