<DOCNO> XIE19970519.0059 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Trade Surplus More Than Doubles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, MAY 19 (Xinhua) -- With the weaker yen promoting
exports, Japan's trade surplus more than doubled in April from a
year earlier, the Finance Ministry announced on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Figures released on Monday showed that Japan's overall trade
surplus surged 163.7 percent, the highest growth rate since
January 1992.
</P>
<P>
Japan's exports in April soared 21.5 percent to 4429.26 billion
yen (38.5 billion U.S. dollars) amid strong exports of automobiles
and office supplies.
</P>
<P>
April imports rose 8.1 percent to 3597.78 billion yen (31.6
billion dollars), because of a 34.1 percent increase in crude oil
imports.
</P>
<P>
The sensitive surplus with the United States shot up even more
strongly, rising 174.1 percent to 468.97 billion yen (4.1 billion
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The trade surplus with the European Union (EU) and Asian
countries in April also rose after a one-month interval.
</P>
<P>
The surplus with the EU expanded 151.3 percent to 230.89
billion yen (two billion dollars), and that with other Asian
countries grew 34.1 percent to 536.56 billion yen (4.7 billion
dollars), the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
Japan's trade surplus began growing in February for the first
time in 27 months and kept rising in March.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said a relatively weaker yen compared with the
exchange rates a year earlier had fueled a rise in exports,
pushing up Japan's surplus, and they cited a possible resurgence
of trade frictions with the United States.
</P>
<P>
They predicted that a similar jump in the trade surplus was
unlikely to be repated in the near future, because the yen's
exchange rate had rebounded on the currency market.
</P>
<P>
Tsutomu Makino, Vice Minister of Japan's Ministry of
International Trade and Industry (MITI) told a press conference
that the ministry will closely monitor the trade surplus for the
time being. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
