<HEADLINE> Badminton Worlds Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GLASGOW, Scotland, May 19 (Xinhua) -- World Badminton
Championships Notebook:
</P>
<P>
Oddest Scottish Import
</P>
<P>
It could be the oddest Scottish import for the year 1997.
</P>
<P>
The organzing committee of the largest ever world badminton
championships ordered 200,000 shuttlecocks for the competition
from a company in Taipei.
</P>
<P>
Half of the goods, each of which is made of 16 feathers, have
just arrived via London in time.
</P>
<P>
-----------
</P>
<P>
High Cost and TV Blackout
</P>
<P>
The Scottish organizers know very well that it will cost them
one million pounds to stage the Sudirman Cup and the world
individual championships.
</P>
<P>
They also know Glasgow City Council paid 300,000 pounds to the
International Badminton Federation to secure the event and the
Scottish Sports Council scooped a big chunk of 196,000 pounds of
its lottery award in recognition of its status.
</P>
<P>
But they could not forsee the nonchalance of the local
television stations as they would not broadcast a single minute of
the event.
</P>
<P>
BBC Scotland say the problem is the dearth of its resources, as
they have soccer, tennis and golf commitments. Scottish Television
said they were never reached while organizers contended contacts
were made even two years ago.
</P>
<P>
----------
</P>
<P>
Fan Power Needed: Scottish Coach
</P>
<P>
Scottish coach Dan Travers sent out a plea to Scottish
badminton fans to come out and support his team.
</P>
<P>
Playing in Division three, the team has no chance to win a
medal but Travers still needs fan power.
</P>
<P>
The Scots meet India in their opening match Monday night
against India. And Travers pleaded, "It is a tough draw and we
need the home support behind us.
</P>
<P>
"I can also promise the fans that the standard of play is
something they will never get a chance to see again," added
Travers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
