<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysian Investment in Southern Mogadishu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, May 19 (Xinhua) -- The Somali faction led by Ali
Mahdi Mohamed in north Mogadishu today asked the Malaysian
government to suspend their investment programs being carried out
in the south of the city.
</P>
<P>
The investment to one of Mogadishu's factions is encouraging
the renewal of fighting over economical interests in the capital,
he said in a press statement.
</P>
<P>
The statement came after Somali-Malaysian Commercial Bank Ltd.
was inaugurated ten days ago in south Mogadishu, the first
foreign-invested bank there.
</P>
<P>
Seventy percent shares of the bank belong to Malaysian
businessmen while the rest of 30 percent to sympathizers of
warlord Hussein Mohamed Aidid.
</P>
<P>
Malaysians have also established a large telecommunication
center in south Mogadishu and seem to enjoy mild relations with
south Mogadishu merchants.
</P>
<P>
The statement warned that such activities will undermine
confidence to future relations with the Malaysian government by
the rest of the Somali communities.
</P>
<P>
The statement even characterized Malaysia's investment as a
move deliberately taken towards further foreign intervention into
Somalia's internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
It urged Malaysians to play a proper role in reconciling the
Somali factions or providing an equal assistance to the different
parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
The statement also praised the Malaysian government for
actively participating in the U.N. failed operation in Somalia.
</P>
<P>
"The Malaysians should not destroy their previous reputation
in the Somali community," said the statement. 
