<HEADLINE> India Can Draw 10,000 mw Power from Neighbors in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, May 19 (Xinhua) -- India can draw a total of 10,000
mw power during the current fiscal year 1997-98 from Pakistan,
Nepal, Bhutan and Bangladesh and this would provide an immediate
solution to the country's power deficit, said a study today by the
Federation of Indian Chambers of Commerce and Industry (FICCI).
</P>
<P>
The projected drawal of power from these countries could touch
20,000 mw by the end of 1998-99, it said.
</P>
<P>
A power grid of the South Asian Association for Regional
Cooperation (SAARC), which embraces Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, the
Maldives, Nepal, Pakistan and Sri Lanka, would be set up for
exchange of power between the SAARC member countries, Indian Power
Minister S. Venugopalachari said here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
India had decided to purchase 3,000 mw surplus power from
Pakistan being generated from the hydel resources of the Indus
river basin, he said, adding that discussions would be initiated
at the foreign secretary level soon as a follow up to the SAARC
summit in Male on May 12-14, where a formal agreement for sharing
the natural resources of the SAARC region had been arrived at, he
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
