<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UAE Banks' Capital Continues to Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, May 19 (Xinhua) -- Capital of the banks in the
United Arab Emirates (UAE) continued to increase last year due to
an impetus from a booming credit market, according to an official
report obtained here today.
</P>
<P>
The shareholders' equities of the Gulf country's 47
commercial banks grew to 6.34 billion dollars at the end of
1996, compared with 5.88 billion dollars at the end of 1995
and 5.42 billion at the end of 1994, said the report issued
by the UAE'S Central Bank.
</P>
<P>
The bulk of the increase came from 19 national banks,
which raised capital to 5.04 billion dollars at the end of
1996 from around 4.16 billion at the end of 1994, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
Bankers said the increase was mainly facilitated by a surge in
the credit market which boomed over the past years.
</P>
<P>
Figures by the central bank showed credits provided by the
47 banks grew to around 25.9 billion dollars by the end of
1996 from 24.9 billion at the end of 1995.
</P>
<P>
The surge came following an upturn in trade and construction
activities due to higher government expenditures and stronger
private participation.
</P>
<P>
Bankers said high credits has allowed most UAE banks to
make record earnings in 1996, with the net profits of 15
out of the 19 national banks in 1996 peaking at 623 million
dollars.
</P>
<P>
They said that the capital increases are expected to
continue this year because many banks had raised more money
and others are following suit to maintain their share of the
credit market in line with the introduction of new lending
rules by the central bank.
</P>
<P>
This would obviously promote the UAE banks to further boost
their financial resources so that they can obtain more
opportunities to provide loans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
