<HEADLINE> Qatar Signs 750 Million Dollars Deal With US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, May 19 (Xinhua) -- To further expand investment and
utilization of its natural resources, Qatar has signed with a
U.S. petroleum company an agreement to set up a 750-million-dollar
petrochemical complex.
</P>
<P>
The deal was singed by the Qatar General Petroleum Corp
and U.S.-based Phillips Petroleum Co. in Doha on Sunday. The Qatar
General Petroleum Corp will hold 51 percent and Phillips 49
percent of the equities in the joint venture, Khaleej Times,
a UAE newspaper, reported today.
</P>
<P>
The project is designed to produce 500,000 tonnes of
ethylene and 467,000 tonnes of polyethylene a year, including
high-density polyethylene and low-density polyethylene, the
newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The project, which is expected to go on stream in 2000,
will also include a Hexene-1 plant with an annual capacity of
50,000 tonnes. Products by the complex will be sold to
consumers in Asia, Europe, the Middle East and Africa.
</P>
<P>
The agreement is regarded as another step to enhance the
policy pursued by Qatar to expand investment and utilization of
its natural resources.
</P>
<P>
The new complex is the gas-rich state's third petrochemical
complex to cash in on its massive gas reserves -- the third
largest in the world after those in Russia and Iran. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970519.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mekong Development Needs Public-Private Partnership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 19 (Xinhua) -- The development of the Great Mekong
Subregion in Southeast Asia needs the increased cooperation
between the public and the private sectors, an Asian Development
Bank (ADB) official said here today.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the 30th International General Meeting of the
Pacific Basin Economic Council, ADB Vice President Bong-Suh Lee
said the main challenge now facing the Mekong area was the
shortage of sufficient financial resources for development.
</P>
<P>
The Great Mekong Subregion, which covers China's Yunnan
province, Myanmar, Laos, Thailand, Cambodia and Vietnam, is
becoming a new economic growth area in Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
To harness the region's full potential for development, the ADB
has begun to identify, design and finance some projects for the
area since 1992. In the past few years, it has provided 318
million U.S. dollars in both technical assistance and loans.
</P>
<P>
However, the cost of the identified priority projects far
exceeds what the six countries (which the Mekong River traverses)
and the bank can contribute in the near future, Lee said.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, critical private sector financing must be sought to
fund these projects, he said, adding that the private sector was a
huge pool of capital while the governments and donor agencies have
limited funds.
</P>
<P>
For this purpose, Lee said, the bank has held a series of
private sector seminars to inform private financial institutions
and investors of the opportunities in the Great Mekong Subregion.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the bank is also studying various options for
absorbing public and private capital, encouraging policy and
regulatory reforms to promote public-private sector cooperation
and redesigning some of the projects to attract the participation
by private investors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970519.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Needs 440 Million Dollars a Year for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 19 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria needs about 440 million U.S.
Dollars a year for basic urban services to keep up with future
population growth.
</P>
<P>
This is the conclusion of a series of workshops held between
May 5 and May 14 in Lagos and four other Nigerian cities, with
the attendance of experts from both the World Bank and Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
Experts say Nigeria's urban population now stands at 45
million and has been growing at 5.5 percent a year since 1980.
</P>
<P>
From 1989 to 1995, the World Bank has lent 878 million Dollars
to infrastructure projects in Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
Nontheless, experts found out that "all types of
infrastructure in Nigeria suffer from massive backlogs of
neglected rehabilitation and maintenance, not to speak of the
investment needed for future growth".
</P>
<P>
Experts identified three options for Nigeria to mobilize the
huge resources needed for infrastructure, including the
concentrating of public funds on projects with high social and
economic impact, encouraging the participation of private sector
as well as non-government organizations.
</P>
<P>
In the long term, experts recommended the selling-off of
loss-making public enterprises, creating a better environment for
private investment and establishing more predictable revenue
flows to states and local governments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
