<HEADLINE> Mugabe says Zairean Situation Improved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, May 19 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe
said the Zairean situation had improved considerably when meeting
with former Australian Prime Minister Bob Hawke in Harare today.
</P>
<P>
Hawke, who is on a visit to cement relations between Australia
and Zimbabwe, paid a courtesy call on Mugabe to renew their
acquaintances and relationship.
</P>
<P>
"Really I think it's for the better for Mobutu. For over three
decades he has done absolutely nothing to develop that country
other than amass wealth for himself."
</P>
<P>
Mugabe, however, expressed hope that the southern African
region should now use its influence on new Zairean leader
Laurent-Desire Kabila to ensure peace in the region.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe praised South African President Nelson Mandela, who
begins a three-day state visit here today for his role, in trying
to bring about a peaceful negotiated settlement to Zaire.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe said the former Australian premier's visit had come at
a time when the southern African region has gone through crucial
economic and political changes.
</P>
<P>
He said he could not forget steps taken by Hawke during his
tenure and Brian Mulroney of Canada in the peaceful negotiations
and attempts at ending apartheid in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Hawke told reporters that he maintained a very close
relationship with Mugabe since his tenure of office as Australian
Premier from 1983 to 1991.
</P>
<P>
He said he had reminisced about their days in the Commonwealth
when they worked very closely together in bringing an end to
apartheid rule in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Hawke said they had discussed developments in the region,
especially Zaire, which he said Mugabe was very optimistic about
the future.
</P>
<P>
He said relations between Australia and Zimbabwe were
excellent although there was room for improvement in the area of
trade.
</P>
<P>
Hawke said he was also in Zimbabwe with some Australian
friends to prepare for the opening of a Shona Sculpture Gallery
in Melbourne later this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
