<HEADLINE> Roundup: Indian Congress Party's Organizational </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, May 19 (Xinhua) -- The Congress Party's
organizational elections have run into serious trouble with
various Indian state units being riven with factional differences.
</P>
<P>
Demands are being made for Sonia Gandhi, widow of India's
former prime minister Rajiv Gandhi, to become active in the
organization and take over the leadership.
</P>
<P>
The alleged manipulation in Congress organizational elections
in some state units appears to be boomeranging with Punjab Pradesh
Congress President Santokh Singh Randhawa quitting Sunday and
several prominent leaders from different state units hitting back
at the party leadership accusing partisan conduct of polls.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with the Election Commission's direction, all
political parties in the country should complete their
organizational elections by the end of May.
</P>
<P>
The Congress Party is one of the two parties asking for 15 days
more to complete its organizational election. The Congress Party
had time and again extended its election time due to differences
within the party.
</P>
<P>
Punjab Pradesh Congress chief Santokh Singh at a press
conference Sunday alleged bogus voting in over 10,000 primary
units and he appealed to Sonia Gandhi to take over party
leadership.
</P>
<P>
He said that he had brought this to the notice of party
President Sitaram Kesri and party General Secretary Nabi Azad, but
they had paid no heed to this "genuine grievance".
</P>
<P>
Even Kesri's home state Bihar appeared to be in crisis with two
known Kesri-baiters, Jagannath Mishra and S.S. Ahluwalia, asking
Kesri to immediately intervene in the polls because serious
irregularities were being committed. One million bogus members had
been enrolled after March 8, the last date for filing membership
form and fee.
</P>
<P>
In the background of the party differences, Sonia was gradually
becoming the focal point of all the "aggrieved" Congressmen.
</P>
<P>
While Madhya Pradesh Chief Minister Digvijay Singh and West
Bengal Youth Congress President Mamata Banerjee met with Sonia
last week and urged her to save the party by taking "active
participation" in the party's organizational affairs.
</P>
<P>
Another party senior leader A.R. Antulay categorically said
that he would withdraw from the contest if Sonia Gandhi became the
party president.
</P>
<P>
The Election Commission has reset the deadline for
organizational elections for June 15. Elections for the Congress
president are slated for June 9.
</P>
<P>
As soon as Rajiv Gandhi was assassinated in 1991, the party had
asked Sonia to become its president, but she declined.
</P>
<P>
Since then she has spurned several offers and preferred to be
away from active politics. Her recent enrollment as the Congress
Party's primary member has inspired the rank and file of the
party, whose image has been seriously damaged due to corruption of
party officials and failure in the general election held in
April-May last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
