<HEADLINE> Mubarak Leaves for Germany on Official Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 19 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
left here today for a visit to Germany to promote bilateral ties
and seek Bonn's counsel on breaking the Mideast peace deadlock,
the Egyptian Middle East News Agency (MENA) reported today.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak, accompanied by a high-powered delegation including
Foreign Minister Amr Moussa, is expected, during his two-day
visit, to hold talks with German President Roman Herzog and
Chancellor Helmut Kohl on means of rejuvenating the peace march.
</P>
<P>
Cairo-Bonn relations at the ministerial level are strong,
according to Egyptian ambassador to Germany, Mahmoud Mubarak,
referring to four meetings in six months between Moussa and his
German counterpart Klaus Kinkel.
</P>
<P>
However, reported misunderstanding arose between the two
countries because of the recent German abstention on a U.N. vote
on a draft resolution denouncing Israel's construction of a
settlement in Arab Jerusalem early this year.
</P>
<P>
Kinkel, during his visit to Egypt early this month, cleared the
atmosphere by elaborating on the motives for the abstention and
emphasizing Germany's opposition to Israeli settlement expansion.
</P>
<P>
In addition to talks on the peace process, the two sides will
also discuss means of boosting bilateral economic ties and
Egypt's bid for associateship with the European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
Egypt has been working for a partnership with the EU, but
disputes over its agricultural exports to Germany, Spain and
Italy have obstructed the deal.
</P>
<P>
Germany ranks the second after the U.S. in terms of Egyptian
imports, and Germans make up 11 percent of the total tourists
visiting Egypt every year.
</P>
<P>
Germany has contributed to the establishment of a plant to
manufacture buses and another to make Mercedes and BMWs, in
addition to their enormous investments in such areas as power,
oil and pharmaceutical industries.
</P>
<P>
It is the second largest donor country to Egypt, with an
annual contribution of nearly 200 million Deutsche Marks (more
than 118 million U.S. dollars), including 180 million Deutsche
Marks (about 106 million dollars) for development and 20 million
Deutsche Marks (11.7 million dollars) for technical cooperation.
</P>
</TEXT>
