<HEADLINE> Syrian Vice-President Arrives in Kuwait </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, May 19 (Xinhua) -- Syrian Vice-President
Abdul-Halim Khaddam arrived in Kuwait today on a Gulf tour which
has already taken him to Qatar and Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
Accompanied by Syrian Foreign Minister Farouq al-Shara,
Khaddam is here to convey a letter to Kuwaiti Amir Sheikh Jaber
al-Ahmed al-Sabah from Syrian President Hafez al-Assad, a local
radio report said.
</P>
<P>
The letter is believed to deal with the deadlocked Middle
East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Khaddam is also scheduled to meet the Kuwaiti amir and Acting
Prime Minister and Foreign Minister Sheikh Sabah al-Ahmed
al-Jaber al-Sabah on the peace process which has been suspended
since Israel started the construction of a Jewish settlement in
its occupied East Jerusalem in March, in defiance of strong Arab
opposition and wide international criticism.
</P>
<P>
Syria is in a drive to drum up support for the Arab parties
in the peace process against the Israeli policy. As part of the
drive, Khaddam and Shara were in Qatar and Saudi Arabia Sunday
for similar talks.
</P>
<P>
In the Qatari capital of Doha, the Syrian official asked the
oil-rich Gulf state to delay its hosting the fourth Middle East
and North African economic conference, originally scheduled in
Doha in November.
</P>
<P>
The previous three conferences were separately held in
Casablanca of Morocco in 1994, Amman of Jordan in 1995, and Cairo
of Egypt in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Qatar, which has frozen normalization of ties with Israel,
said earlier the conference would be held as scheduled but gave
no assertion whether Israel would be invited.
</P>
<P>
Syria is seeking to delay the convention of the conference
before a possible breakthrough in the stalemate of the Middle
East peace process.
</P>
<P>
In Saudi Arabia, the Syrian vice-president conveyed a similar
message to King Fahd ibn Abdul-Aziz and held talks with Saudi
government officials on the same issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
