<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Diamond Giant Re-opens Buying Office in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 19 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's biggest
diamond manufacturer De Beers's Central Selling Organization
(CSO) has re-opened its diamond buying office in Zaire, De Beers
announced today.
</P>
<P>
De Beers does not yet mine diamonds in Zaire, but the CSO has
marketed one-third of the country's production.
</P>
<P>
"We are asked to open the office in Mbuji-Mayi about two weeks
ago," spokesman Tom Tweedy said.
</P>
<P>
The move signals an apparent change of approach to the CSO by
Zaire's self-proclaimed President Laurent Kabila.
</P>
<P>
Kabila's top aid Mwana Nanga Mawampanga said last month in
Lubumbashi, the second largest city in Zaire, that he was not
happy with De Beers' monopoly position in the diamond industry
and planned to renegotiate contracts with international mining
companies.
</P>
<P>
"We are relieved the situation in Zaire has come to a peaceful
end...We very much want to be a part of the country's future and
are anxious to establish formal cooperation as we had before,"
Tweedy said.
</P>
<P>
"The nature of Zairean production makes us confident that the
logic of the world diamond marketing situation will prevail, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Zaire produces six percent of world diamond output by value.
According to industry sources, Zaire's total official diamond
production is worth around 450 million U.S. Dollars a year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
