<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tree-Planting Helps South China City's Economic Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, May 19 (Xinhua) -- A decade of afforestation is
reported to have contributed a great deal to the economic growth
of Jiangmen, in south China's Guangdong province.
</P>
<P>
Jiangmen is the ancestral home of many overseas Chinese and was
recently listed as one of the top ten cities in China in terms of
economic and social development. This attributed in large part to
the city's tree-planting efforts which begun in 1985, according to
Gu Rixin, the city's party secretary.
</P>
<P>
"Afforestation helps control soil erosion and thus helps
agricultural production. In 1994, although the region was hit by
consecutive days of torrential rains, there was still a good
harvest because the forest greatly reduced the effects of the
floods," he explained.
</P>
<P>
He said the afforestation has also helped clean the Tanjiang
River near Jiangmen. According to the Guangdong provincial
environmental protection departments, the Tanjiang River is one of
the cleanest rivers in Guangdong.
</P>
<P>
"Without the good environment created largely by the
afforestation efforts, the overall economy in Jiangmen would not
have developed so fast, and local residents' standard of living
would be significantly affected," Gu said.
</P>
<P>
At present 85 percent of the land around Jiangmen has been
planted and the tree-coverage rate in the region has reached 43
percent, much higher than the national average. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
