<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East Asian Games Concludes in Pusan with Success </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PUSAN, May 19 (Xinhua) -- The second East Asian Games was concluded
here on Monday with success as the athletes and officials from nine
participating countries and regions bade farewell with smiles in face.
</P>
<P>
South Korean prime minister Koh Kun declared the closing of the
East Asian Games this evening at the Kudok Stadium.
</P>
<P>
"The citizens of Pusan and all Koreans sincerely hope that the
second East Asian Games have promoted the Olympic movement, and will
help East Asia reinforce peace and unity," said Kim Un-yong, president
of the organizing committee of the second East Asian Games.
</P>
<P>
Kim said that "the energy you have expended and the sweat that you
have shed here in Pusan will not fade away from our memory, and
friendship which have been forged in competition will also remain
forever in our memory."
</P>
<P>
"I believe that the Olympic spirit which has built a brighter and
healthier life must be spread further to build a better and more
peaceful world," Kim said.
</P>
<P>
The host took the last gold medal in the soccer tournament for a
total of 45 gold medals to rank third behind China and Japan.
</P>
<P>
China retained its top spot with 62 golds against 47 for Japan,
while Kazakhstan who made its debut in the games, garnered 24 titles
from a bonanza of 187 events in 13 sports at the 10-day sports gala.
</P>
<P>
"The East Asian Games featured first-class tough competitions in
Asia, and our Chinese athletes had exploited the great opportunity to
whet their weapons for future international sports meets with the
Bangkok Asian Games and the Sydney Olympic Games in particular," said
Wu Shaozhang, chef de mission of the Chinese delegation.
</P>
<P>
Okai Yoshiro, chef de mission of the Japanese squad, said "we had
surpassed our goals of gold medals in both swimming and athletics
competitions and we extend our sincere gratitude to the organizing
committee, the Korean Olympic Committee and all the cooperative Pusan
citizens."
</P>
<P>
The Japanese swimmers boasted of the lion's share of 21 out of 31
gold medals from the swimming finals while their athletes took home 16
out of 43 golds from the track and field competitions.
</P>
<P>
Choi Hyun-yol, chef de mission of the South Korean delegation,
explained that the hosts failed to overtake Japan for the second
over-all place in the gold tally "because China did not send in
first-class swimmers in the games."
</P>
<P>
South Korea ranked third by a slim margin of two golds against
Japan that will play the host of the third edition in Osaka in 2001.
</P>
<P>
Chinese man gymnast Zhang Jinjing, individual fourth-placer in
Atlanta Olympic Games, became one of two quadruple champions at the
10-day games by spearheading his teammates to capture the gymnastics
team title apart from taking the men's individual all-around, parallel
bars and horizontal bar crowns.
</P>
<P>
Japanese swimmer Takashi Yamamoto was the other quadruple champions
at the games who won two team finals apart from the men's 100m and
200m butterfly.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese also set the Asian record of 1:58.01 in the men's 200
meter butterfly, the lone record in the swimming pool.
</P>
<P>
Five world records were overwritten by four Chinese strongwomen of
Song Zhaomei, Yu Wenyu, Jiang Yinsu, Zou Feie and Chinese strongman
Wang Guohua.
</P>
<P>
Mongolia won its first three gold medals at the regional meet
through the wrestling competitions, while both Guam and Macao also
struck their first and lonely bronze medal in Taekwondo and Wushu
respectively.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
