<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Testosterone Test to Be Used By IOC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, May 19 (Xinhua) -- The International Olympic Committee
(IOC) will introduce this year a test for testosterone,
International Amateur Athletic Federation (IAAF) spokesman Giorgio
Reineri said here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The new test will detect if a female athlete has taken the male
sex hormone testosterone.
</P>
<P>
At present athletes are suspended if their urine sample shows
an excessively high ratio of testosterone to epitestosterone. But
the current method does not show if the testosterone has been
introduced artificially.
</P>
<P>
Reineri added that the new test would show definitely if an
athlete had taken testosterone.
</P>
<P>
Reineri said the test could be ready in time for the World
Athletics Championships in Athens in August. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970519.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-19 11:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan's New Press, Publication Law Leads to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, May 19 (Xinhua) -- A new press law has created uproar
in Jordan with the government defending it as safeguarding
national interests and the press saying it will endanger press
freedom.
</P>
<P>
According to the amendments to the 1993 Press and Publication
Law which was enacted by King Hussein Saturday, each violator of
the articles will be fined from 21 U.S. dollars to 35,311 dollars
and some weekly tabloids will be forced to close down.
</P>
<P>
Minister of State for Information Affairs Samir Mutawi
defended the government's decision in a television interview
Sunday by saying that the amendments were necessary because "some
of the papers tried to disrupt the national fabric and harm
Jordan's relations with Arab countries."
</P>
<P>
"We found ourselves committed to saving the country's
national fabric and (then) took the decision," the minister
added in the interview.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the board of the Jordan Press Association submitted
a resignation Sunday in protest of the amendments, saying that
they were brought into force by a temporary law in spite of the
existence of a Lower House still in office and "the spirit of the
law will abolish all press freedoms for journalists."
</P>
<P>
The amendments, the third temporary law introduced under the
currant government of Abdul Salam Majali, not only raise the
fines on violators, but give the court the right to suspend
publication of any paper found in violation of the law.
</P>
<P>
The law is largely understood to target the weekly tabloids,
which have long raised the ire of the government and some
segments of the society by their sensational and often
misleading reporting.
</P>
<P>
The amendments demand that weekly newspapers raise their
capital from about 21,186 dollars to 423,729 dollars and that
the dailies raise theirs from some 70,621 dollars to 847,458
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Justifying the capital requirements, Mutawi said in the
interview that "we heard that some papers have not paid their
staffs for months."
</P>
<P>
Editors of 12 weeklies expressed strong rejection of the
revised law, appealing to parliament, now in recess, to reject
the law and work for its cancellation.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian Weekly Press Committee was prepared to file a
case at the higher Court of Justice if the government does not
act constitutionally on the issue, according to NBidal Mansour,
chief editor of Al Hadath (The Event) Weekly.
</P>
<P>
Now the government controls two of the three most important
Arabic dailies and the only English daily Jordan Times through
holding shares in concerned equity companies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970519.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai to Clear Away Billboards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, May 19 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai, the largest industrial
and commercial center in China, will clear away some advertisement
boards that have gone uncontrolled on some major streets.
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai Municipal People's Congress said that it would
formulate regulations and laws to handle advertising boards that
are erected along sidewalks, as they have been in the way of
pedestrians, posed potential threats to traffic safety, and caused
"visual pollution,"
</P>
<P>
The miscellaneous boards have mainly been erected by government
departments which used their power to set up ad companies to make
money. Meanwhile, some enterprises have also been forced to
advertisement on streets, burdened with extra expenses.
</P>
<P>
So far, 26 lawmakers in the municipality have suggested the
local Administration for Industry and Commerce manage the ad
boards, and urged the municipal People's Congress to pass laws to
deal with the problem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
