<HEADLINE> Tumbling Bank Stocks Drag Australian Stocks Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 19 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market closed
lower today as another wave of profit-taking saw investors abandon
the bank sector amid growing concerns profits have peaked.
</P>
<P>
The bank sector tumbled more than 2 percent as investors turned
their gaze to the resource sector, which rose more than 1.1
percent.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index closed 7.1 points weaker at 2,531.0,
off a low 2,522.9 and its high of 2,538.2.
</P>
<P>
Lance Jones &AMP; Co broker Brett O'Donovan said a key feature of
trading was the switch by investors from industrial stocks,
particularly banks, to resource stocks.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index jumped 16.8 points higher to 1,477.1,
while the all industrials index slumped 33.9 points to 3,910.8.
</P>
<P>
The banking index closed 90.2 points or 2.03 percent down at
4,359.9.
</P>
<P>
Commonwealth Bank shares were the hardest hit, sliding 36.1
cents to 13.759 Australian dollars while NAB fell 25 to 17.70
Australian dollars, Westpac lost 13 to 7.11 Australian dollars and
ANZ dropped 31.3 to 8.017 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index was 14.7 points weaker at 1,559.3 while gold
bullion closed at 343.85 US dollars an ounce from 347.35 US
dollars last.
</P>
<P>
National turnover totaled 315.07 million shares traded valued
at 954.92 million Australian dollars (735.28 US dollars) with
falls outnumbering rises 466 to 303.  
</P>
</TEXT>
