<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, May 19 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items in
leading French newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- The troops of Laurent-Desire Kabila, many of whom are
Rwandans, entered Kinshasa on Saturday without meeting any
resistance. They publicly executed about 100 men and took prisoner
thousands of government troops and suspects. South Africa has sent
its vice president to Zaire to verify the promises for democracy
made by Kabila, and France simply urged the organization of
elections.
</P>
<P>
-- President Jacques Chirac achieved his visit in China by
diving last weekend into the vibrating urban atmosphere of
Shanghai, a city radically transformed by a few years of
modernization with hasty steps and reviving to its old status
which was equal to Paris, New York, or Berlin.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- The troops of Laurent-Desire Kabila complete on Sunday the
job of putting Kinshasa under their total control after the
soldiers of Mobutu laid down their arms without any
fight. According to the Red Cross, 200 people, mostly soldiers and
looters, were killed during the weekend, most often as a result of
settling personal accounts.
</P>
<P>
-- Five public opinion polls published last Saturday showed
that the French center-right alliance and the leftist parties will
run shoulder to shoulder in the first round of legislative
elections. The polls, conducted by five different polling
institutions, showed that the center-right will win from 39
percent to 40.5 percent of the votes, while the left will win from
37.5 percent to 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
But all of them predicted that the center-right will finally
win from 40 to 130 more seats than the left after the second round
of the voting. 
</P>
