<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PBEC Meeting Expresses Confidence in HK's Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 19 (Xinhua) -- The 30th International General
Meeting of the Pacific Basin Economic Council (PBEC), which
formally opened here today, has expressed its full confidence in
the future of Hongkong.
</P>
<P>
In a resolution adopted by its Steering Committee and Board of
Directors Sunday, the PBEC said that it recognizes China's
forthcoming resumption of its exercise of sovereignty over
Hongkong.
</P>
<P>
The resolution, which was released here today, says: "It
believes that under the imaginative concept of 'one country, two
systems,' the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) will
continue to play an important role in the economic development of
China."
</P>
<P>
"PBEC believes that the SAR will maintain its functions as a
significant center for services in the region, and as base of
operations for many of the PBEC member companies," the resolution
says.
</P>
<P>
It says that PBEC would like to congratulate all parties
concerned for "their efforts in making a smooth handover
possible," and expresses "its heartfelt wishes to the authorities
and the people of Hong Kong for a most successful and promising
future."
</P>
<P>
The three-day meeting will discuss a wide range of issues, such
as the regional economic cooperation and the liberalization of
trade and investments in the region.
</P>
<P>
Founded in 1967, PBEC serves as a forum through which regional
business leaders create new business relationship and address
emerging issues in the Pacific and global economies.
</P>
<P>
PBEC is composed of over 1,200 companies in 20 member economies
-- Australia, Canada, Chile, China, Colombia, Ecuador, Fiji, Hong
Kong, Indonesia, Japan, South Korea, Malaysia, Mexico, New
Zealand, Peru, the Philippines, Russia, Chinese Taipei, Thailand
and the United States.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
