<DOCNO> XIE19970519.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese and French companies to jointly produce corn products </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, May 19 (Xinhua) -- A Sino-French joint venture is
set to process 300,000 tons of corn annually when its first-phase
project is completed in 1999.
</P>
<P>
A foundation laying ceremony was held recently in Songyuan city
in northeast China's Jilin Province to mark the beginning of the
construction of the project, which is jointly funded by Chinese
Jifa Group Company and French Eridania Beghin-Say S.A.
</P>
<P>
The first-phase project, requiring an investment of more than
1.4 billion yuan, will mainly produce glucose and maltose. It is
expected to yield a sales income of 1.1 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Jilin is a major grain production base in China, turning out
annually some 1.5 million tons of corn. The joint effort is
expected to ease the province's difficulty in grain sales,
transportation, and storage.
</P>
<P>
Jifa Group Company, the largest corn processor in Asia, has
total assets worth four billion yuan and is capable of processing
600,000 tons of corn annually. Ericania Beghin-Say S.A. is the
largest agricultural by-product producer in Europe and reports an
annual sales volume of 12 billion US dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970519.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inner Mongolia Becomes China's Major Power Supplier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, May 19 (Xinhua) -- North China's Inner Mongolia
Autonomous Region has developed a total power generating capacity
of 6.2 million kw and is one of the country's largest power
suppliers.
</P>
<P>
Presently, the region has become a major power supplier for
China's Northeast Power Grid, the Beijing-Tianjin-Tangshan Power
Grid, and Mongolia.
</P>
<P>
According to a local source, Inner Mongolia started supplying
power to Beijing in 1990. And by 1995, it had provided for Beijing
an annual power supply totaling 6.48 billion kwh, accounting for
one fourth of Beijing's total power consumption.
</P>
<P>
Inner Mongolia now ranks first in the country in terms of
average per capita electricity output and the amount of power
supply to other localities.
</P>
<P>
The local source said that the region has rich resources for
developing its power industry, for it has five extra-large coal fields
with reserves totaling more than 100 billion tons.
</P>
<P>
Since the autonomous region practised systematic power reform
and pooled funds for power construction in 1986, the region's
power sector has been developing steadily. A large number of power
projects have been built since then.
</P>
<P>
The local source expects that by the year 2000, the region's
total installed power generating capacity and electricity output
will hit 15 million kw and 54.6 billion kwh respectively.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970519.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northwest China Region Getting More Migrant Farmers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, May 19 (Xinhua) -- A phenomenon similar to that of the
building sites of Beijing or south China's booming areas where
waves of migrant workers come looking for jobs is taking place in
northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region where an
increasing number of migrant farmers are looking for work -- but
in the cotton fields.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of thousands of surplus labor from inland rural areas
are coming to Xinjiang during the region's cotton harvest
time. Some of the cotton pickers come in the fall and go back in
early spring, while others stay on as caretakers in cotton fields.
</P>
<P>
"Picking cotton or even growing cotton in Xinjiang is our best
choice," said 23-year-old Yang Kunlun, a migrant farmer from
southwest China's Sichuan Province.
</P>
<P>
Yang and his wife went to Bachu County in the Tarim Basin in
southern Xinjiang last September and earned more than 4,000 yuan
picking cotton all autumn. The money was equal to Yang's entire
income for five years back home.
</P>
<P>
The couple took over the job of managing a four-ha plot of
cotton in February. According to their contract, the employer will
pay them 7,200 yuan by the end of August when the cotton picking
begins.
</P>
<P>
Some earlier arrivals are even more ambitious and have made
enough money and gained enough experience picking up cotton over
the past few years that they have begun to grow cotton all by
themselves.
</P>
<P>
Seven years ago, Yu Bishuang and his wife came to Shache,
China's largest cotton producing county, also in the Tarim Basin,
where he worked at a brick kiln for four years. He planted about
two-thirds of a hectare of cotton on a contract deal in 1995, but
he didn't make any money because of his ignorance about cotton
growing.
</P>
<P>
But, practice makes perfect, and Yu got a contract on two ha of
land last year, and to his astonishment, made a profit of more
than 30,000 yuan.
</P>
<P>
"We've decided to expand our growing area bit by bit. If no
more land is available in this township, we will go to another
place," Yu said.
</P>
<P>
Xinjiang is rich in land resources with a high degree of
mechanization of agriculture, and local township or village
officials are keen on teaching farmers how to grow cotton, his
wife explained.
</P>
<P>
The autonomous region is China's largest cotton producer,
accounting for a quarter of the national output, and its cotton
production has become a major contributor to local economic
development and has lined farmers' pockets.
</P>
<P>
"Migrant farmers have made a great contribution to our cotton
growth. It's no easy job for them to leave their hometowns and
work with us," notes Ahmad Shamushak, head of Kalatale Township in
Aksu city in the western part of Xinjiang. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
