<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Investment Area to Be Launched Next Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, May 19 (Xinhua) -- The ASEAN Investment Area
(AIA) is expected to be launched towards the end of next year to
facilitate investments into the ASEAN region under the ASEAN Free
Trade Area (AFTA), according to Malaysian Deputy Minister of
International Trade and Industry Kerk Choo Ting.
</P>
<P>
The AIA is aimed at enabling free flow of capital among ASEAN
member countries and facilitating access to technology and skilled
personnel and professionals in ASEAN besides calling for a larger
ASEAN private sector role in matters relating to investment
activities, Kerk said at a seminar on "The AFTA Challenge: Getting
SMIs Ready" in Shah Alam near here today.
</P>
<P>
He said the AIA would cover aspects relating to investment
promotion, facilitation and liberalization.
</P>
<P>
It has been agreed that ASEAN would undertake a coordinated
effort in promoting ASEAN as a regional investment location,
emphasizing the benefits to be gained by investors who take a
regional approach in investing in the region, he said.
</P>
<P>
In the pursuit of a free and open investment regime, member
countries -- Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, Singapore, the
Philippines, Thailand and Vietnam -- would consider opening all
industries to ASEAN investors as well as to investors from outside
the region, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian official said the AIA, which would pursue a
liberalization approach, is likely to be less structured,
emphasizing unilateral actions by member countries and covering
both investments in the manufacturing and the non-manufacturing
sector.
</P>
<P>
Under the Common Effective Preferential Tariff (CEPT) scheme's
"Fast Track Program", existing tariffs above 20 percent would be
reduced to 0-5 percent by January 1, 2000, and those at 20 percent
and below, would be reduced to 0-5 percent by January 1, next
year, he said.
</P>
<P>
Under the "Normal Track Program," tariffs above 20 percent
would be reduced in two stages: First, to 20 percent by January 1,
next year and subsequently to 0-5 percent by January 1, 2003; And
at the second stage, tariffs of 20 percent and below will be
reduced to 0-5 percent by January 1, 2003.
</P>
<P>
In terms of intra-ASEAN trade value, the sectors which would
have an average ASEAN tariff of 0-5 percent by the year 2000 are
the machinery and electrical appliances, mineral products, base
metals and metal articles, textile and apparel and chemicals.
</P>
<P>
Other sectors which would have an average ASEAN tariff of 0-5
percent by the year 2000 are plastics, pulp and paper, cement and
ceramics, gems, optical and musical instruments, antiques and
works of art, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Sectors with an average ASEAN tariff of above 5.0 percent are
prepared foodstuffs, wood, footwear, arms, and miscellaneous
articles," he added.
</P>
<P>
To assist the Small Medium Industries (SMIs) to prepare
themselves for the AFTA, the ASEAN Industrial Cooperation (AICO)
scheme was created in April last year and came into effect
November 1, last year, where cooperative efforts were being
undertaken in services, intellectual property rights, investment
and industrial cooperation, with tremendous response from the
member countries, Kerk said.
</P>
<P>
The scheme, aimed at promoting joint-manufacturing activities
between ASEAN-based companies, eliminates or reduces intra-ASEAN
tariffs by granting to qualified participating companies
immediately, zero or up to a maximum of 5.0 percent CEPT tariffs
for imports of approved AICO products, instead of the prevailing
CEPT rates which would reach the final range of 0-5 percent by the
year 2003.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970519.0141 </DOCNO>
