<HEADLINE> Liberian Elections Rescheduled for July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, May 19 (Xinhua) -- The presidential and parliamentary
elections in Liberia, originally scheduled for the end of this
month, has been postponed to July, the Punch newspaper reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Nigerian Foreign Ministry sources as saying
that a specific date will be decided by a meeting of foreign
ministers of the Economic Community of West African States
(ECOWAS) opening in Abuja today.
</P>
<P>
ECOWAS Chairman and Nigerian head of state General Sani Abacha
met with Liberian leaders last week in Abuja to discuss the
request by 11 Liberian parties to shift the elections.
</P>
<P>
The meeting reached a consensus on the need to grant the
Liberian independent electoral commission enough time to prepare
for the elections, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the commission Henry Andrews was said to have
requested for 56 to 60 more days to set things in order.
</P>
<P>
Presidential candidate of the All Liberian Coalition Party
Alhaji Kromah on Sunday described the meeting with Abacha as
satisfactory. 
</P>
