<HEADLINE> Israel Not to Escalate Lebanon's clashes: Defense </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 19 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak
Mordechai indicated Sunday night that Israel has no intention to
escalate the tensions in south Lebanon, reported the state-run
Israel Radio.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai made the remarks after vising a soldier wounded
during last Thursday's clashes north of the Israeli self-styled
security zone.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai declared that the Israel Defense Forces (IDF) had
not defined the Lebanese government standing army as enemy. He
was referring to an allegation that the gunmen of the Lebanese
guerrilla group were aided by Lebanese troops during the
fighting, in which three Israeli soldiers were killed and seven
others wounded.
</P>
<P>
However, Mordechai warned that the IDF will continue to
return fire on anyone who shoots at its soldiers.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, the head of the IDF Northern Command,
Maj.-Gen. Amiram Levine, said that it was the Lebanese army, not
Hezbollah, who fired anti-aircraft missiles at Israeli
helicopters during the fighting. He added that the Hezbollah
gunmen only had fired mortars and machine guns.
</P>
<P>
Levine told reporters that the IDF will continue to initiate
operations in north of the Israeli occupied "security zone,"
wherever and whenever necessary.
</P>
<P>
He also warned that all those who tried to hit the IDF would
themselves be hit, including the Lebanese Army.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, The Israel Air Force warplanes blasted Hezbollah
targets in southern parts of Lebanon's Bekaa Valley for the
third day running following Thursday's clashes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
