<DOCNO> XIE19970519.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-19 07:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Official: Oslo Peace Agreement Broken Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 19 (Xinhua) -- A senior United States official
has said that the 1993 peace deal reached at Oslo of Norway
between the PLO and Israel's former government has foundered.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a U.S.-Israeli Chamber of Commerce meeting late
Sunday night, U.S. Ambassador to Israel Martin Indyk said that
"the core bargain of Oslo, (according to which) Israel was
promised security and the Palestinians were promised
self-government, has broken down."
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu, who also attended
the meeting, said in response that trust resides in keeping deals,
while he accused the Palestinians of violating the accords that
Israel observed.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, U.S. National Security Adviser Samuel Berger brushed
off a Palestinian call for President Bill Clinton to make a
dramatic intervention in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
"Presidential involvement is happening every day," Berger said
on CNN, the U.S. Cable News Network. "And the parties themselves
have to be prepared to make the kinds of compromises, the kinds of
commitments, that would make a dramatic moment not only dramatic
but successful."
</P>
<P>
Palestinian National Authority President Yasser Arafat sent
Clinton a letter Friday, declaring U.S. special envoy Dennis
Ross's latest mission a failure and asking the U.S. head of state
to intervene personally in Israeli-Palestinian talks.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Israeli defense officials said Sunday
that plans to raze hundreds of illegally-built Palestinian homes
in the West Bank were being carried out, and it was not a part of
a new program to prevent Palestinians from creating facts on the
ground ahead of the resumption of final status negotiations.
</P>
<P>
"There are certainly hundreds of structures, not all of them
built this year, which are in the process of legal proceedings to
be demolished because they are illegally-built," said Shlomo Dror,
spokesman for the coordination of activities in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Israel demolished 140 homes last year and this
year 80 were destructed so far, while, He ruled out the
possibility of destroying another 500 by the end of the year, as
Israel Radio had reported.
</P>
<P>
Dror said the Palestinian homes planned for destruction were
usually considered a security risk since they are near military
bases, bypass roads, or Jewish settlements.
</P>
<P>
"There are illegal houses throughout the area under our
authority," said Peter Lerner, spokesman for the Israeli Civil
Administration in the West Bank, "but there is no new plan to
demolish 500 houses."
</P>
<P>
He added, however, that there were ongoing plans to demolish
"hundreds" of homes built without authorization and that these
plans were approved regularly by Israeli Defense Minister
Yitzhak Mordechai.
</P>
<P>
All the homes were in the Israeli-controlled area C, he said.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Arafat presented Ross a list of 1,300 families who
had received demolition orders, and Ross was reportedly surprised
at the size of the list and raised the matter later in his
meeting with Mordechai. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
