<DOCNO> XIE19970519.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Increasing Protection of Cultivated Land (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 19 (Xinhua) -- China says that strict measures
must be taken to implement its basic state policy of "treasuring
and rationally using every inch of land, and earnestly protecting
cultivated land".
</P>
<P>
"Protecting cultivated land is safeguarding our lifeline," it
says in a document published by all the leading newspapers here
today.
</P>
<P>
This comes from a notice issued Sunday by the Chinese Communist
Party Central Committee, and the State Council, the country's
highest governing body.
</P>
<P>
Indiscriminative use of cultivated land, illegal approval of
land use, and waste of land resources have been rampant in some
parts of the country over the past several years, the document
points out.
</P>
<P>
"The sharp decrease in cultivated land and loss of land assets
have seriously affected grain production, agricultural
development, the national economy, and social stability." it says.
</P>
<P>
Land management, especially the protection of cultivated land,
has a vital bearing on the whole situation of the country and the
country's generations to come, it stressed.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, effective measures must be taken to check the trend
of imbalance between increasing population and heavy loss of
cultivated land, the seven-part document added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970519.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Increasing Protection of Cultivated Land (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Efforts must be made to intensify macro control of land
management, the notice said, adding that various provinces,
autonomous regions, and municipalities must increase the total
acreage of cultivated land and, at the same time, improve the
fertility of the soil.
</P>
<P>
The decrease and increase in the acreage of cultivated land
must reach a balance point, and to do so, provinces, autonomous
regions, and municipalities must co-ordinate their use of
cultivated land for other purposes with the reclamation of
cultivated land, it said. New land utilization plans must be drawn
up scientifically and old ones revised, and then they must be
strictly applied, it stressed.
</P>
<P>
The use of cultivated land for construction projects must be
strictly controlled, and plots of land currently being used for
construction projects and waste land must be more effectively
used, the notice said.
</P>
<P>
While the agricultural structure is being readjusted, land not
under cultivation should be used better. Cultivated land is not to
be taken over for developing forestry, orchards, or fish ponds if
it is not needed for improving environmental conditions.
</P>
<P>
Measures should be taken to improve the management of the land
use plans, and the governments all areas should follow the Basic
Farmland Protection Regulations, the notice said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970519.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Increasing Protection of Cultivated Land (4) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The management of collectively-owned land in rural areas must
be improved, the notice pointed out. There should be better plans
for village and town construction and for barren mountainsides and
idle land. Arable land that is left over from changes in villages
and townships should be reclaimed, it added.
</P>
<P>
Construction of residential areas in rural areas should follow
village and town construction plans. There is only one plot of
ground allowed for residence per family and the acreage must not
top the stipulated norm. Additional plots should be turned over to
collectives in accordance with the law, the notice said.
</P>
<P>
Cultivated land can not be left idle. Contracts for land rights
are no longer valid if a farmer is no longer engaged in
agricultural production or if he or she fails to carry out the
terms of the contract, it added.
</P>
<P>
There must be a change in funeral and interment practices, and
cremation is considered preferable, it said, adding that villages
in mountainous areas can set up a public cemetery, while those on
the plains can build a crematorium where funerary urns can be kept
in one place.
</P>
<P>
Tombs that occupy cultivated land or wooded areas should be
properly handled with, and efforts should be made to persuade
those families involved to move the tombs or to bury coffins
deeper down, it said.
</P>
<P>
Township enterprises should protect and preserve cultivated
land, it added.
</P>
<P>
New materials should also be used for walls so that the
production of clay bricks can be limited, and the construction of
kilns on cultivated land is banned. Brick kilns that occupy
cultivated land must be moved for land reclamation, it said.
</P>
<P>
Except in the case of state requisition, collectively-owned
land use right is not allowed to be sold or used for commercial
development, or to be transferred or leased for non-agriculture
construction, it stressed.
</P>
<P>
Land use right of collectively-owned barren land can not be
auctioned and leased for non-agriculture development.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970519.0157 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Increasing Protection of Cultivated Land (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Approval procedures for use of land for construction purpose
must be stricter, the document said. From now on, the country is
putting a one-year freeze on the use of cultivated land for
non-agricultural construction projects, and projects that call for
the use of cultivated land will have to get approval from the
State Council, it pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Housing construction for low-income families in urban areas and
state-approved projects can continue to use land in accordance
with the previous regulations, it said.
</P>
<P>
There must be strict controls on the scale of land use in urban
construction, especially in small and medium-sized cities. From
now on there will be a freeze on the practice of upgrading
counties to city status, it added.
</P>
<P>
Urban construction projects should make better use of land
potential by utilizing land that is not cultivated and by
improving land use efficiency, it noted.
</P>
<P>
Changes in city planning must get approval from the proper
authorities, it said, adding that in large cities, the amount of
land used for construction and the population growth must be put
under control by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The power for land management and land use rights can not be
delegated, it stressed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970519.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Increasing Protection of Cultivated Land (6) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Any profit from previous construction work will be given to
local governments for developing urban infrastructure or land, or
for improving low-yield farmland, the notice said, adding that any
profit from changing farmland into non-farmland will be turned
over to the central government for the development of cultivated
land.
</P>
<P>
Government at all levels, and financial and supervisory
departments should monitor and manage gains from land more
carefully to prevent the loss of land assets, it said.
</P>
<P>
The enforcement of land management must be increased, the
document said. Governments should do a thorough check on land that
has been used for construction projects and plots that have been
taken over for residential construction in rural areas since 1991,
it added. This check, which should be completed by the end of
October, should include the following:
</P>
<P>
-- Development zones unauthorized by the State Council or the
provincial government must be stopped and be used for
farming. Development zone projects that have been approved by the
authorities but have not been developed as planned will be subject
to penalties;
</P>
<P>
-- Land taken for commercial real estate projects and golf
courses should be dealt with;
</P>
<P>
-- A thorough check should be made on the transfer, leasing, or
mortgaging of land-use right. Illegal land speculation is to be
strongly penalized; and
</P>
<P>
-- The use of land occupied by township enterprises, villages,
or residential buildings in rural areas should be standardized.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970519.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Increasing Protection of Cultivated Land (5) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The management of state-owned land assets should be improved,
the notice said. There should be stricter control on the random
transfer of land use right of cultivated land. Land use right of
cultivated or arable land, and of wooded areas is not to be
claimed for developing golf courses, classical-style parks,
recreation centers, luxury villas, or ancestral halls, temples, or
churches, it pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The sale of state-owned land right is to be done through a
system of public bidding to ensure fair play, the notice said. The
country should use a system that starts with the lowest land price
possible, and the price of state-owned land-use right for auction
should be set through scientific evaluation in accordance with
state policy, it added.
</P>
<P>
The sale of land use right of military zones, or key areas
under state protection or areas of national security, and projects
that involve large tracts of land for overseas investors must get
approval from the State Council, it said. Land-use right for an
entire island can not be sold to foreigners, it stressed.
</P>
<P>
The country will also require businesses that have acquired
free land-use right from the state for non-agricultural projects
to pay for those right, it said.
</P>
<P>
State-owned enterprises that have become corporations or have
issued shares must pay for land that was previously appropriated
by the state, after the price of the land has been established, it
said.
</P>
<P>
China will also standardize the practice of transferring land
use right and will penalize the illegal transfer of land by
speculation, it stressed.
</P>
<P>
Land-use right of state-owned land that is bought can not be
transferred if the land has not been developed or used in
accordance with the terms and conditions of the sale agreement, it
said, adding that illegal transfers will be penalized and any
profit made from it will be confiscated. The transfer of
state-owned land use right must be registered, and unregistered
transfers are considered illegal and will be penalized.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970519.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Increasing Protection of Cultivated Land (7) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The central authorities are also urging land departments to
establish a nationwide land management information system using
modern technology to keep a closer watch on land use, it said.
</P>
<P>
Efforts should be made to improve the organizing and guiding
work of the land management, the notice said.
</P>
<P>
The land issue has a direct bearing on the national interests
and must be in accord with the unified managment of the state, it
said.
</P>
<P>
Governments at all levels need to place great importance on
land management and support the work of land management
departments. The people should be made more aware of basic state
land-use policies, the document stressed.
</P>
<P>
And finally, Party committees and governments at all levels
should come up with land protection measures and report these
measures to the central authorities by the end of next month, the
notice said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
