<HEADLINE> Malaysia-China relations "Very Good": Malaysian FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, May 19 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Foreign Minister
Abdullah Ahmad Badawi has described Malaysia-China relations as
"very good" based on his talks with Chinese Vice Premier and
Foreign Minister Qian Qichen.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah, who recently concluded a four-day official visit to
China, said in a statement issued here by the Foreign Ministry
today that bilateral ties had considerable prospect of being
strengthened further through more cooperation in air services,
tourism, culture and education, trade and investment.
</P>
<P>
He described his visit as "extremely useful and successful"
during which he also called on Chinese President Jiang Zemin and
Premier Li Peng.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah said the objective of his trip was to exchange views
with his counterpart on bilateral relations, get an update on
China's economic reform and explore the possibilities for more
economic and business ties and to promote further ASEAN-China
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
He said both countries shared the view that it was very
important for China to succeed in its economic modernization.
</P>
<P>
He said Malaysia welcomed the considerable progress that China
had made in its economic reform and reiterated that such a
development would greatly contribute to peace and stability,
particularly in the region.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah said he also renewed his Prime Minister Mahathir
Mohamad's invitation to Li Peng to visit Malaysia while Malaysian
King Tuanku Ja'afar would visit China in July this year.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian foreign minister said that the second ASEAN
(Association of Southeast Asian Nations) informal summit would be
held here in December, for which Mahathir, in his capacity as the
chairman of the summit, would be extending the official invitation
to China, Japan and South Korea shortly.
</P>
<P>
In view of ASEAN's 30th anniversary this year, the informal
meeting is also expected to see for the first time the gathering
of the heads of state and government from the seven ASEAN
countries and the grouping's three prospective members --
Cambodia, Laos and Myanmar -- besides China, Japan and South
Korea.
</P>
<P>
He said he believed the summit would be able to provide further
impetus to peace and stability in the Asia-Pacific region and
bring regional cooperation to greater heights.  
</P>
