<HEADLINE> Zambian Women Build Castor Oil Factory </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, May 19 (Xinhua) -- A women's club in Central Province
of Zambia has built a factory to produce castor oil, Times of
Zambia reported today.
</P>
<P>
Grace Lusenga, the head of the Mikula Women's Club, said in an
interview with the local newspaper the construction of the
factory which started in 1995 is expected to finish soon and
operate from September.
</P>
<P>
Lusenga said that the club received a grant from the African
Development Fund in 1994 after acquiring a 25-hectare piece of
land.
</P>
<P>
The club cultivates 11 hectares of castor beans and sunflower
from which oil will be extracted and sold to local industries.
</P>
<P>
She said that the club expects to raise a lot of money from
sales of the oil so as to explore other business ventures.
</P>
<P>
The club with a membership of about 30 women, has also used
part of the grant to start a tailoring shop to sell clothes to
the locals. 
