<DOCNO> XIE19970519.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pacific Basin Economic Council Meeting Opens in Manila </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 19 (Xinhua) -- About 600 local and foreign business
leaders gathered here today for the 30th International General
Meeting of the Pacific Basin Economic Council (PBEC), which will
focus on issues reflecting changes in business climate in the
Pacific area.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening plenary session, Philippine President
Fidel Ramos praised the 20-member economic body for being a
pioneer in promoting economic and trade cooperation in the region.
</P>
<P>
He also lauded the group for creating a forum for "the active
exchange of views among businessmen to advise their governments
and international agencies on a wide spectrum of economic issues
and concerns affecting the region's development."
</P>
<P>
Ramos expressed the hope that the PBEC, with 30 years of
experience in bringing business and government together, will help
in building a new partnership between business and government for
the common future of the Asia-Pacific community.
</P>
<P>
The theme of the three-day annual meeting is "Pacific In
Transition: Adapting to a Changing Business Environment."
</P>
<P>
High on the meeting's agenda are issues pertinent to free trade
and investment, barriers to open banking and financial services,
relations between technology and business, and implications of
regional security and continued economic development.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will give PBEC members a chance to evaluate and
analyze the results of the Asia Pacific Economic Cooperation
(APEC) leaders meeting in Manila last November and the World Trade
Organization (WTO) ministerial meeting in Geneva last December.
</P>
<P>
Also attending the meeting will be WTO Director General Renato
Ruggiero, Chinese Vice Premier Li Lanqing, Malaysian Deputy Prime
Minister Anwar Ibrahim and Hong Kong Chief Secretary Anson Chan.
</P>
<P>
Founded in 1967, the PBEC is an association of business leaders
from over 1,200 companies in the Pacific. It aims to expand trade
and investment through open markets and encourage competitiveness
based on the capabilities of the individual companies.
</P>
<P>
The PBEC, the oldest business organization in the Pacific rim,
serves as a forum through which regional business leaders create
new business relationships and address emerging issues in the
Pacific and global economies.
</P>
<P>
The organization, an informal recommendatory body to the APEC,
also serves as a liaison between business leaders and government
officials.
</P>
<P>
Its member economies include Australia, Canada, Chile, China,
Colombia, Fiji, Hong Kong, Indonesia, Japan, South Korea,
Malaysia, Mexico, New Zealand, Peru, the Philippines, Russia,
Chinese Taipei, Thailand, the United States and Ecuador.
</P>
<P>
Ecuador was accepted as the 20th PBEC member Sunday by the PBEC
Steering Committee, which usually meets before the international
general meeting and is empowered to endorse membership.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970519.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Growing of Cash Plants Helps Boost China's Local Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, May 19 (Xinhua) -- The growing of economic plants in
east China's Zhejiang province last year contributed 15 billion
yuan (some 1.8 billion US dollars) to the province's GDP, helping
four mountainous counties to get rid of poverty.
</P>
<P>
With nearly 60 percent of the population living in hilly areas,
the province is rich in forestry resources. According to Li Zemin,
governor of the province, making full use of the forestry
resources is an important step for the province to boost its
overall economy.
</P>
<P>
"Apart from great afforestation efforts over the years, the
development of bamboo products and other economic plants have
been largely enhanced," Li said.
</P>
<P>
Li said that the total bamboo planting area in Zhejiang has
reached 630,000 hectare, yielding 3.5 billion yuan (430 million US
dollars) worth of bamboo products yearly.
</P>
<P>
Last year the total foreign trade volume of forestry
products reached 550 million US dollars, nearly twice that of five
years ago.
</P>
<P>
In Ji'an county where as many as 100,000 farmers are involved
in bamboo planting, bamboo has come to be a pillar of the local
economic development.
</P>
<P>
The total yearly output of the bamboo industry in the county
has reached 1.1 billion yuan (130 million US dollars), earning
15.6 million US dollars in foreign exchange.
</P>
<P>
"Bamboo has played a main role in changing our county from a
poor one into a well-off one," said Xi Caixiang, head of the county,
"now every year as much as 400 million yuan (nearly 50 million US
dollars) of farmers' income in our county derives from the bamboo
industry." 
</P>
</TEXT>
