<HEADLINE> S. Africa Recognizes Zairean New President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 19 (Xinhua) -- South Africa has recognized
Laurent Kabila as the President of "the Democratic Republic of
the Congo", local daily the Citizen quoted Deputy President Thabo
Mbeki as saying today.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki made the announcement in Lubumbashi after meeting with
Kabila over the future of this vast central African country,
otherwise known as Zaire.
</P>
<P>
Kabila proclaimed himself president Saturday, renaming Zaire
the Democratic Republic of the Congo and announced that a
government of national salvation would be formed by May 20 and an
assembly be convened to draft a new constitution within two
months.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki said he was satisfied that the transitional government
would be broad-based.
</P>
<P>
"It is important during this transitional period that the
people should enjoy democratic rights and democratic freedom.
</P>
<P>
"The approach of the alliance to this question is indeed that.
It is itself an alliance of democratic forces," he said.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki, an active participant in the negotiations that led up
to Kabila's taking power, was the first foreign dignitary to see
Kabila since he declared himself president.
</P>
<P>
He spent about two hours with Kabila in Lubumbashi, the
temporary headquarters of Kabila's Alliance of Democratic Forces
for the Liberation of Congo-Zaire. 
</P>
</TEXT>
