<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Has Highest Number of Bankrupts in Region </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, May 19 (Xinhua) -- Singapore has the highest number
of bankrupts per million population in the region, despite a
decline in the numbers of new bankrupt cases within the last three
years, the Business Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
The report said that since picking up in 1993, the number of
people officially declared broke in the year has been falling,
from 1,413 in 1994 to 1,277 in 1995, to 1,252 last year.
</P>
<P>
Also noted in the report was the fact that changes to the
Bankruptcy Act in 1995 resulted in a big jump in the number of
discharged bankrupts to 1,926, from 554 in 1994.
</P>
<P>
At the end of 1996, Singapore had 13,696 undischarged
bankrupts, or 4,033 per million population. This compares with
second-ranking Malaysia's 2,877 per million population. Malaysia
had 57,161 bankrupts at the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
In terms of new bankrupts, Australia tops the region with
17,324 in 1996, while Malaysia is a distant second with 6,139 new
cases last year.
</P>
<P>
Experts said that the high numbers in Singapore, Malaysia and
Australia reflect the efficiency of the bankruptcy process. They
noted that bankruptcy proceedings in these three countries are
relatively inexpensive, swift and certain.
</P>
<P>
The report also noted that an overwhelming number of bankrupts
in Singapore last year were salaried men in their prime of life.
Of the 1,254 new bankrupts in 1996, 88 percent were wage earners,
84 percent were male and 75 percent were aged 30-50.
</P>
<P>
The reasons people get into financial trouble include
overspending on their credit cards, defaulting as guarantors and
failure to pay car loans, the report said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970519.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Trade Grows In East China's Zhejiang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, May 19 (Xinhua) -- East China's Zhejiang province is
recovering from last year's stagnating foreign trade as it
reported a trade volume of 2.61 billion US dollars for the first
quarter of this year, a year-on-year increase of 16.31 percent.
</P>
<P>
Exports were up 35.26 percent, while imports dropped eight
percent, according to the Hangzhou Customs. State-owned foreign
trade enterprises contributed nearly 62 percent of the total, with
1.62 billion US dollars in trade volume.
</P>
<P>
Overseas-funded enterprises also played a role in the increase,
with a total business volume of 859 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Other foreign trade index in the province are showed as follows:
</P>
<P>
--general trade recovered from last year's slump, and made up
56.7 percent of the total in the first quarter;
</P>
<P>
--processing trade maintained rapid growth, accounting for
33.52 percent;
</P>
<P>
--equipment imports of overseas-funded enterprises as part of
their investment dropped by 37.09 percent, due to China's
readjustment of preferential treatment on tariffs;
</P>
<P>
--Japan, the United States, and Hong Kong remain the three
largest trade partners of the province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
