<HEADLINE> India's Textile Exports Achieve Targets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, May 19 (Xinhua) -- India's textile exports have
achieved the target of 11.8 billion US dollars for the year
1996-97, said an annual report just released by the Ministry of
Textiles.
</P>
<P>
The textiles sector in the country has fulfilled the targets
set up for it for the eighth five year plan (from 1992-93 to
1996-97) period in terms of production, exports and other key
parameters. Spun yarn production of 2,380 million kg exceeded the
target of 2,335 million kg in 1995-96, the pre-terminal year of
the plan. Production of cloth, which is estimated at 29,666
million sq. meters, has also surpassed the target of 27,774
million sq. meters by a significant margin, the report said.
</P>
<P>
There has been a notable increase in the production of cotton
which reached 16 million bales during the 1995-96 cotton season.
Keeping all relevant factors in view, a quota of 1.59 million
bales of cotton was released for export during 1995-96.
</P>
<P>
To cope with the demand for silk in both domestic and export
sectors, the government has allowed silk exporters to import raw
materials on a duty-free basis under the advance licensing scheme
for producing exportable silk products, the report further said.
</P>
</TEXT>
