<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India to Seek More Time to Free Imports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, May 19 (Xinhua) -- India is likely to seek seven to
ten years for freeing imports of certain sensitive items, mainly
agricultural products, at the balance of payments consultations
under the aegis of the World Trade Organization (WTO) scheduled
for early June in Geneva, a government official said here today.
</P>
<P>
India is due to submit its phase-out schedule this month. The
Commerce Ministry proposal envisages removal of restrictions in
two phases over five years. In the first phase, items allowed for
import under the special import list (SIL) can be made freely
importable and an equal number of restricted items can be moved
onto the SIL list. Dual use items can also be made freely
importable. In the second phase, the items that remain on the SIL
can be made freely importable.
</P>
<P>
Under the previous export-import policy of the country, the
restricted list consists of 2,500-2,800 items. While 59 items are
prohibited, roughly 650 are on the SIL list and 178 are canalized
items. On the basis of the harmonized code, it has been calculated
that around 70-72 percent of the items are either freely
importable or can be imported under SIL list. Almost 7,000 items
are on the free list.
</P>
<P>
India's major trading partners have been demanding that India
phase out all restrictions within two years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970519.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepali Opposition Slams Government Over Local Polls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, May 19 (Xinhua) -- Nepal's main opposition accused
the government of failing to maintain security and order during
the first phase of local elections held in West Nepal on Saturday,
the local press said today.
</P>
<P>
The Nepali Congress (NC) party in a statement Sunday even
alleged that the government resorted to "state terrorism" to give
a ruling coalition partner an advantage in the elections, the
reports said.
</P>
<P>
Security personnel and election officers were mute observers in
almost all the cases when activists of different political parties
clashed each other at polling stations, the NC party claimed.
</P>
<P>
Most election-related incidents taking place Saturday were
between workers of the NC and the Communist Party of Nepal (United
Marxist Leninist, CPN-UML), according to election officials.
</P>
<P>
The local elections at West Nepal's 146 villages and over 10
municipal wards have been postponed due to these clashes, they
said.
</P>
<P>
Official sources said that two persons were killed Sunday in
separate incidents in two mid-western districts when police opened
fire to control unruly crowds who demanded early vote-counting or
started to loot ballot boxes.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary results of Saturday's local elections showed a
marginal lead by the opposition NC party while much of the ballots
were yet to be counted, newspapers here said.
</P>
<P>
The election results are expected to be officially announced
early next month after the second phase polls in Central and East
Nepal on May 26.
</P>
<P>
The NC party, which currently controls some two-thirds of all
the local administrations in the country, would likely lose
considerable shares to the CPN-UML, the biggest partner of Prime
Minister Lokendra Bahadur Chand's three-party coalition, during
the on-going local elections, analysts here said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
