<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Taipei Wins First Gold in Basketball History </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PUSAN, May 19 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Taipei claimed its first gold
medal in basketball history when it edged South Korea 71-70 in the
men's basketball final on the final day of the second East Asian Games
here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Taipei squad, with all members from its veteran team,
mananged to control the attacking pace in the second half after losing
the first 31-34.
</P>
<P>
Cheng Chih Lung shot 20 points and play maker Chou Chun San had 19
for the winners. Chu Chih Ching, who added 10 points, grabbed 11
rebounds for Chinese Taipei.
</P>
<P>
When being lagged behind at 58-64 with four minutes remaining,
South Korean players increased their speed and narrowed the margin to
61-64 with a three pointer from Cho Sung Won, the only three points he
had in the match.
</P>
<P>
At 17:36, after trailing the score at 63-64, a foul from Chun Hee
Chul of South Korea gave the Chinese Taipei team two free throws from
Chu Chih Ching, who added two points to extend the lead.
</P>
<P>
With 10.3 seconds to go, when Chinese Taipei led the score 70-68,
Woo Ji Won of South Korea had a critical foul and Chou Chun San made
one point from two free throws.
</P>
<P>
With 0.4 seconds remaining, Huang Chun Hsiung made a foul and Seo
Jang Hoon of South Korea improved the score to 70-71 from two free
throws.
</P>
<P>
Guu Jyi Shyong, assistant coach of the Chinese Taipei team, said
the victory was a result of excellent team work.
</P>
<P>
"We showed good team work in the match, and our players had a good
contorl of the pace, especially in the dying miutes," he said.
</P>
<P>
In the play-off for the third place, China defeated Kazakhstan
71-55 to win the bronze medal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
