<HEADLINE> Drug Suspect Wants Quick Extradition to US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, May 19 (Xinhua) -- Alleged drug kingpin Li Yun-chung,
who was arrested in Myanmar and sent back to Thailand last
Saturday, has requested quick passage to the United States to face
drug trafficking charges.
</P>
<P>
Li, who had been arrested in Thailand last July and jumped bail
in February, fears that if he was sent back to prison, his life
would be in danger.
</P>
<P>
A federal court in New York indicted Li on charges of
masterminding the shipment of 486 kilograms of heroin to the
United States in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Li had put up a 5-million-baht guarantee on February 7, but
jumped bail and fled to Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
Police said Li paid 120 million baht (4.8 million US dollars)
to a middle-man to arrange for his freedom.
</P>
<P>
Li is afraid that if he stays in Thailand, even in prison, he
might be killed by those who had helped him, to stop him from
revealing the names of those who had helped him escape.
</P>
<P>
Somchai Udomwong, a deputy chief justice of the criminal court,
is being investigated by a judicial panel for his role in granting
bail for Li.
</P>
<P>
Li would go through legal procedures in criminal court before
he is handed over to the US authority for the extradition.
</P>
</TEXT>
