<HEADLINE> No Troop Pullout from Albania, Says Italian PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, May 18 (Xinhua) -- Italian Prime Minister Romano Prodi
said today that he was not urging a pullout of the Italian-led
Multinational Protection Force (MPF) from Albania.
</P>
<P>
Prodi said this following press reports that Italy was in favor
of withdrawing the MPF if Albanian leaders did not resolve their
political stalemate.
</P>
<P>
"There was no threat of a pullout, just a serious observation,"
Prodi told reporters during a visit to the northern Italian city
of Modena today.
</P>
<P>
"I wanted to indicate to Albanian leaders that the
international community is involved in an operation that demands a
response from the whole of Albanian society," said Prodi, adding
that "without such a response our job grows more difficult."
</P>
<P>
Albania's reconstruction cannot begin until all parties
accepted the need for compromise to arrive at an election law,
Prodi stressed.
</P>
<P>
Albanian Prime Minister Bashkim Fino told reporters in Tirana
that he was seeking to avoid the fall of his government of
national unity because he was convinced there was no alternative.
</P>
<P>
If he were to resign, "We would be back to where we were on
March 9 and that means the brink of a civil war," said Fino.
</P>
<P>
He said his government was continuing to press for accord on an
electoral law so that elections could take place on June 29 as
scheduled.
</P>
<P>
Fino said he would like to see the MPF extend its role to cover
"election infrastructure, that is, guard polling stations."
</P>
</TEXT>
