<HEADLINE> More Foreign Exchange Trade For Chinese Port City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, May 19 (Xinhua) -- Residents of north China's port
city of Tianjin have become active traders at the local foreign
exchange market since the beginning of the year.
</P>
<P>
The city branch of the Bank of China reports that the number of
foreign exchange deals by individual investors rose 30 percent in
the middle of May of this year, a turnover that amounted to 56
percent of last year's total for the entire year.
</P>
<P>
The bank began its foreign exchange business in 1995, and
individuals are allowed to trade in US dollars, yen, marks, pound
sterling, and Hong Kong dollars. Last year, 80 percent of the
trade was quoted in dollars and yen, but mark, pound sterling, and
Hong Kong dollar deals have been on the rise this year.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here attribute the brisk trade in foreign exchange to
a significant increase in income in the city and to the growing
number of contacts between people here and overseas.
</P>
<P>
The analysts noted that a good record of stability in the
national foreign exchange market has also encouraged residents to
invest in hard currencies.  
</P>
</TEXT>
