<HEADLINE> Violence Colors Election Campaign in Indonesian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, May 19 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's ruling party Golkar's
election campaign in the capital city of Jakarta on Sunday was
colored by violence in several areas but security officers were
able to take the situation under control immediately.
</P>
<P>
Jakarta police chief Major-General Pol. Hamami Nata said here
today that even though violence took place in a number of places,
security situation remained within the tolerable limits.
</P>
<P>
He said that there were no dead or injured victims in the
violence and so far police had not detained anybody.
</P>
<P>
There is no report on losses incurred but many cars were
damaged as they were hit with stones thrown by rival contestant
supporters who pelted with each other.
</P>
<P>
The violence happened when the convoys of Golkar supporters
passed on the streets and were stoned by onlookers from the
road-sides who were believed to be supporters of the United
Development Party (PPP).
</P>
<P>
In old Kebayoran market violence caused a lot of damage to
several shops and their windows were broken, a report said.
</P>
<P>
Witnesses said police had to fire some warning shots into the
air to break up the brutal mass.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's three political parties -- the United Development
Party (PPP), the Golkar and the Indonesian Democratic Party (PDI)
-- have been campaigning since April 27 for the general election
on May 29. The campaign will end on May 23.
</P>
<P>
They will vie for 425 seats of the 500 parliamentary seats. The
remaining 75 seats are reserved for the military who do not vote
in the election.
</P>
<P>
In this year's campaign, the country is divided into three
groups of campaign areas where the three parties could do their
campaign activities in turn.
</P>
<P>
About 124 million voters are eligible to take part in the
election, the sixth one since 1971 in the country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
