<HEADLINE> Nachagyn Bagbandy Elected Mongolia's New President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ULAN BATOR, May 19 (Xinhua) -- Nachagyn Bagbandy of the
People's Revolutionary Party was elected president in Mongolia's
presidential election Sunday, defeating incumbent President
Punsalmaagiyn Ochirbat.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary results showed Bagbandy had won 60.79 percent of
the.
</P>
<P>
Under Mongolian law, a candidate who gains more than half the
votes will become the president.
</P>
<P>
President Punsalmaagiyn Ochirbat, from the ruling Democratic
Union Coalition of the National Democratic Party and the Social
Democratic Party, collected 29.8 percent of the votes, Election
Committee Chairman Lhagvasuren told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Bagbandy will be sworn in as president in one month.
</P>
<P>
Bagbandy, born in 1950 in the county of Yaruu, Zavhan Province,
graduated from the Moscow Academy of Social Sciences in 1987.
</P>
<P>
He served as chairman of the Great Hural (parliament) from July
1992 to July 1996.
</P>
<P>
Some 85 percent of the 1.1 million eligible voters turned out
in this second direct election in the country. Final results were
expected only after vote-counting was completed in remote rural
areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
