<HEADLINE> Yunnan Puts In Huge Funds to Tackle Dianchi Lake Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, May 19 (Xinhua) -- The governments of Yunnan province
and Kunming city are to spend 110 million yuan (13.7 million US
dollars) to stop waste water being discharged into the Dianchi Lake.
</P>
<P>
At present, 500,000 tons of waste water are flowing each day
into the Dianchi Lake, the sixth largest freshwater lake in China
and a major source of tap water for the city of Kunming.
</P>
<P>
A Yunnan official said that after the local government-funded
projects are completed next year, the flow of sewage will be
checked.
</P>
<P>
The projects include the installing of pipelines and building
of pumping stations and sewage treatment plants along the rivers
that connect to the Dianchi Lake.
</P>
<P>
Dianchi Lake, 300 square km in space, is one of China's 13
lakes and rivers that enjoy state-level protection. Yunnan
Province and Kunming City have collected money and used World Bank
loans to tackle its pollution in the past few years.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last year, three sewage treatment plants with a
daily capacity of 210,000 tons had been built around the lake.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970519.0196 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand's Shrimp Exports Decrease </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, May 19 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's shrimp exports decreased
in 1996, but the country remained the world's largest shrimp
exporter, and the biggest supplier of shrimp to the United States
for the six straight year.
</P>
<P>
The figures issued by the Business Economic Depart of the Thai
Commerce Ministry showed the value of Thai shrimp export in 1996
was 43.3 billion baht (1.7 billion US dollars), down 14 percent
from 50.3 billion baht (2.01 billion US dollars) in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The export volume last year was 161,486 tons, a decline of 7.7
percent from the 174,974 tons recorded the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Exports to the United States and Japan alone totaled 106,101
tons, or 65.7 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
The United States imported 72,711 tons from Thailand in 1996,
while Japan imported 288,763 tons from Thailand.
</P>
<P>
In January this year, the United States imported 6,622 tons
from Thailand, an increase of 16.43 percent from January 1996.
</P>
<P>
Japan imported 6,259 tons from Thailand in January this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970519.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-19 </DATE_TIME>
