<HEADLINE> Russia Remains Opposed to NATO's Expansion, Says Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, May 18 (Xinhua) -- Russia remains opposed to NATO's
eastward expansion but will seek to develop political and economic
relations with the organization, said a senior Russian official
today.
</P>
<P>
Aleksiej Salmin, Russian President Boris Yeltsin's advisor, was
speaking at a three-day international seminar on European
security, which ended here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
He said that most people in Russia are opposed to the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO)'s eastward expansion, although
they could not hold back the process. Russia will seek to develop
political and economic relations with its neighbors to offset the
effect of the expansion.
</P>
<P>
A Ukrainian representative said his country supported the idea
of cooperating with NATO, but differed on the question of NATO's
eastward expansion and Ukraine's joining the organization.
</P>
<P>
A Polish representative said Poland's joining NATO does not
mean to isolate Russia. Poland wished to develop good relations
with its neighbors including Russia.
</P>
<P>
Over 30 representatives from Russia, the United States, NATO,
the European Union and 10 East European countries participated in
the seminar. 
</P>
