<HEADLINE> More Companies Means More Jobs For Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, May 19 (Xinhua) -- Enterprises, with investment from
other parts of the country and ministries of the central
government have provided 250,000 job opportunities in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
According to a recent survey, about 10,000 enterprises, funded
by 29 provinces and municipalities outside Shanghai have
created 70,000 job opportunities for the local residents.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the state ministries opened more than 300
companies in Shanghai offering 180,000 job opportunities.
</P>
<P>
The survey showed that 85 percent of the companies, with
investment from outside Shanghai are doing businesses in service
sector, such as transportation, construction and decoration, real
estate, software development, wholesales and retails.
</P>
<P>
Many of the enterprises, run by the state ministries are large
industrial enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The registered fund of the companies, run by outside municipal
cities and provinces has surpassed 15 billion yuan (about 1.8
billion US dollars), according to the survey sponsored by the
city's planning committee.
</P>
<P>
The registered fund of the companies, run by state ministries,
has reached 50 billion yuan (about six billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The survey also found that about two-thirds of those companies
were founded after the establishment of Pudong area in Suburban
Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
Experts said the investment from outside Shanghai has effected
satisfactory returns.
</P>
<P>
For example, a car assembly factory, opened in Pudong by the
First Automotive Group of Northwest China's Jilin province, had a
registered fund of six million yuan (723,000 US dollars). In 1995,
it produced about 13 million yuan (1.6 million US dollars) in
revenue, and in 1996, it turned over 15 million yuan (1.8 million
US dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
