<HEADLINE> Shanghai Sees Heavy Foreign Exchange Trading By Individuals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, May 19 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai residents are investing
heavily in the foreign exchange trading market. The foreign
currency turnover by individual investors surged 66.32 percent
over the first quarter last year, according to the Shanghai-based
Bank of Communications.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that the two major factors behind the active
trading is the rapid growth of individual income and a wider range
of choices in making investments.
</P>
<P>
They said that some stock investors are channeling their money
from the stock market to the foreign currency market, in fear of the
mounting risks in stock investment because of high prices.
</P>
<P>
Foreign exchange transactions were first opened to individuals
in Shanghai in 1993. The local branches of Bank of China and Bank
of Communications are the only two institutions authorized to
offer such service.
</P>
<P>
The monthly growth of individual trading volume with the Bank
of Communications Shanghai branch then surged from the 28.11
percent to 105.45 percent during the first quarter this year.
</P>
<P>
Almost half of the transactions during the first quarter were
conducted through telephones, since the bank opened telephone
trading service and extended service hours for such trading till
night earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
Analysts also said Shanghai people have displayed their wisdom
in taking advantage of the international change of exchange rates,
judging from the fact that most of the transactions took place in
wildly fluctuating foreign currencies for the first three months
this year.
</P>
<P>
Foreign exchange transactions were first opened to individuals
in Shanghai in 1993. The local branch of the Bank of China is
another bank authorized to offer the service. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
