<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Sets Goal for Developing Animal Husbandry Next Century </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, May 19 (Xinhua) -- By the year 2000, an average Chinese
is expected to consume 53 kilograms of meat, 17 kilograms of eggs
and eight kilograms of dairy products a year, the Ministry of
Agriculture predicted here today.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has therefore worked out a plan for the
development of animal husbandry for the early next century, a
ministry official revealed.
</P>
<P>
According to the plan, he said, the overall production of meat,
eggs, and dairy products across the country should respectively
reach 68 million, 22 million and 10 million tons at the turn of
the century.
</P>
<P>
By the year 2010, the production shall be further increased to
84, 25, and 21 million tons, which means that every Chinese citizen
can eat 60-kg meat, 18-kg eggs and 15-kg dairy products each year.
</P>
<P>
The state has also decided that the proportion of the animal
husbandry output value to the overall agricultural output value
should increase by one percentage point every year, to reach 35
percent by 2000 and around 50 percent by 2010, the official said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
