<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Background: ABCs of Basic Law of Hong Kong SAR (91-92) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 19 (Xinhua) -- Following are the ABCs of the Basic
Law of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (91-92) in a
question-and-answer format:
</P>
<P>
Question: Will Hong Kong be able to maintain and develop
relations with foreign countries on its own after 1997?
</P>
<P>
Answer: Hong Kong will become a special administrative region
of China when the Chinese government resumes its exercise of
sovereignty over the region. Hong Kong, therefore, will not be
permitted to maintain and develop diplomatic relations with
foreign countries and regions on its own.
</P>
<P>
This in no way means that the Hong Kong SAR cannot have
relations and exchanges with foreign countries. It means rather
that the Hong Kong SAR should maintain and develop relations with
foreign countries under specified conditions and circumstances
under the principle of safeguarding national sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
For example, the Hong Kong SAR may, using the name "Hong Kong,
China," maintain and develop relations, and conclude and implement
agreements, with foreign states and regions and relevant
international organizations in economic, trade, banking, shipping,
telecommunications, tourists, cultural, sports and other
appropriate fields.
</P>
<P>
Question: Will Hong Kong residents be able to visit foreign
countries and regions after 1997 by using passports of the Hong
Kong SAR?
</P>
<P>
Answer: Article 154 of the Basic Law states that the central
government will authorize the government of the Hong Kong SAR to
issue, in accordance with law, passports of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region of the People's Republic of China to all
Chinese citizens who hold permanent identity cards of the Region,
and travel documents of the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region of the People's Republic of China to all other persons
lawfully residing in the Region.
</P>
<P>
Such passports and documents are valid for all states and
regions and record the holder's right to return to the Region. The
goverment of the Hong Kong SAR may apply immigration controls on
entry into, stay in and departure from the Region by persons from
foreign states and regions.
</P>
<P>
Various countries and regions are eager to do business with
Hong Kong and the Chinese mainland, and businesspeople from all
over the world would like to have the convenience of visiting Hong
Kong without having to obtain visas. With assistance and
authorization from the central government, the Hong Kong SAR
government may conclude agreements on not requiring visa with
foreign states or regions. This also provides great convenience
for Hong Kong people.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
