<HEADLINE> Jiangsu to Clean Up Taihu Lake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 19 (Xinhua) -- By 2010, Taihu Lake water will be
drinkable under a Jiangsu Province plan to clean up the lake,
today's "China Daily" reports.
</P>
<P>
To fully carry out this "clean water" project, an investment of
6.76 billion yuan (814.8 million US dollars) is needed between
1996 and 2000.
</P>
<P>
Taihu is one of the country's three big freshwater lakes with
most of its basin in Jiangsu Province. More than two-thirds of the
lake is now saturated with pollutants.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, the country included the lake as a priority project
for pollution control for the Ninth Five-Year Plan (1996-2000).
</P>
<P>
The effort will make the water reach State first-grade
standards by 2000, and between 2000 and 2010, 90 percent of the
sewage from cities and townships in its basin should be treated
and 30 percent of the dispersed waste water point sources in rural
areas should be treated.
</P>
<P>
By 1998, the province will order the 241 sources of pollution
near the lake to take measures to control their pollution or face
closure within time limits.
</P>
<P>
Cities and counties by the lake are required to set up 43
sewage treatment plants, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Experimental zones with eoncologically freindly projects will
be set up in most of the lake basin to cut the quantity of run-off
chemical fertilizers by 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
And rivers flowing into the lake and the whole lake area will
be comprehensively tackled. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970519.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nachagyn Bagbandy Elected Mongolia's New President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ULAN BATOR, May 19 (Xinhua) -- Nachagyn of the People's
Revolutionary Party was elected president in Mongolia's
presidential election Sunday, defeating incumbent President
Punsalmaagiyn Ochirbat, preliminary results show.
</P>
<P>
Under Mongolian law, a candidate who gains more than half the
votes will become the president.
</P>
<P>
Bagbandy garnered more than 60 percent of the votes, the
preliminary results show.
</P>
<P>
President Punsalmaagiyn Ochirbat, from the ruling Democratic
Union Coalition of the National Democratic Party and the Social
Democratic Party, received 30 percent of the votes.
</P>
<P>
Bagbandy, born in 1950 in the county of Yaruu, Zavhan Province,
graduated from the Moscow Academy of Social Sciences in 1987.
</P>
<P>
He served as chairman of the Great Hural (parliament) from July
1992 to July 1996.
</P>
<P>
Some 80 percent of the 1.1 million eligible voters turned out
in this second direct election in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
