<HEADLINE> Utah's Karl Malone Wins NBA MVP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, May 18 (Xinhua) -- Utah Jazz power forward Karl
Malone edged out Chicago Bulls superstar guard Michael Jordan to
win the National Basketball Association (NBA)'s Most Valuable
Player Award on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Malone received 986 points and 63 first-place votes, compared
to 957 points and 52 first-place votes for Jordan, from a panel of
sports writers and broadcasters throughout the United States and
Canada.
</P>
<P>
Detroit Pistons forward Grant Hill finished third with 376
points, followed by Miami Heat guard Tim Hardaway (238), Charlotte
Hornets forward Glen Rice (134) and Seattle SuperSonics guard Gary
Payton (105).
</P>
<P>
Malone, whose previous high finish in MVP voting was third in
1988-89 and 1994-95, averaged 27.4 points, 9.9 rebounds and a
career-best 4.5 assists in leading the Jazz to a franchise-best
64-18 record this season.
</P>
<P>
He shot 55 percent from the field and 76 percent from the free
throw line. Malone ranked second in scoring, sixth in field goal
percentage and 11th in rebounding. 
</P>
</TEXT>
