<HEADLINE> Major News Items In Leading Australian Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 19 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading Australian newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
The Australian
</P>
<P>
-- Prime Minister John Howard sought to reassert his leadership
authority yesterday, promising fundamental tax reform after the
next election, and to consider any further labor market reform
short of cutting minimum wages.
</P>
<P>
The Sydney Morning Herald
</P>
<P>
-- The International Olympics Committee will pressure
Australian officials this week to have the curfew at Sydney
Airport lifted for several days before and after the 2000 Olympics
and provide more high quality hotel accommodation.
</P>
<P>
The Age
</P>
<P>
-- Prime Minister John Howard yesterday increased speculation
that he may call a double dissolution election if the Senate
refuses to endorse his legislation on native title.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Financial Review
</P>
<P>
-- Taxpayers will no longer be able to claim a tax deduction
for bribes paid to foreign government officials, the federal
government announced.
</P>
<P>
The move brings Australia into line with the increasingly
widespread practice among OECD countries of denying a bribery tax
deduction to companies paying bribes as part of their business
transactions in foreign countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
