<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-18 17:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait, US Sign Arms Funds Investment Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, May 18 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait and the United States
today signed an agreement to enable the Gulf state to invest its
funds, earmarked for purchasing ordered American weapons, in the
U.S. in coordination with the U.S. Federal Reserve Board.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, Kuwait's quarterly payments for the U.S.
military equipment ordered through the Foreign Military Sales
program will be placed with the U.S. Federal Reserve until the
cash is demanded by the contractor, the official Kuwait News
Agency said.
</P>
<P>
It said the agreement is between the government of Kuwait
and the government of the United States and it covers all
purchases from the U.S. under the Foreign Military Sales
program.
</P>
<P>
Placing the funds with the Federal Reserves will mean that
Kuwait receives a fixed return on the funds until they are
made over to the contractor.
</P>
<P>
The investment will be in U.S. treasury bonds and some
banks' deposits in coordination with the Federal Reserve Board.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was stricken within a framework of bilateral
relations, official sources said.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait ordered five Patriot batteries and 210 missiles under
the program from the U.S. in 1992 and signed a 11.4
million U.S. dollars contract with the American Raytheon
Corporation last October for two Patriot missile sites. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
