<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF to Help Developing Countries Out of Heavy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, May 18 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary
Fund (IMF) today pledged to help developing countries
out of heavy indebtedness.
</P>
<P>
Talking to representatives of women non-governmental
organizations (NGOs) in the city today, IMF Deputy Managing
Director Alassane Ouattara said economies of most African
countries are facing a heavy debt burden.
</P>
<P>
He said the IMF and the World Bank are working out means that
would assist developing nations bring debts to sustainable
levels.
</P>
<P>
Ousttara, who arrived here on Saturday for a three-day
official visit, commended Tanzania for its implementing reforms
that have enable the country's economy to grow.
</P>
<P>
The IMF deputy chief said, however, that there is a lot to be
done to achieve macro-economic stability, adding that he is
optimistic that the government would achieve its goal in bringing
down inflation to single digit levels.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania's rate of inflation was around 30 percent in 1955.
Tight control of government spending and aggressive collection of
revenue helped bring down inflation to 13.8 percent as of
February, this year. However, drought that hit many parts of the
country pushed up inflation to 17.5 percent in March.
</P>
<P>
Ouattara said that IMF is encouraged with the on-going reforms
in the country, including plans to introduce the Value Added Tax
(VAT) and a stock exchange.
</P>
<P>
Later the IMF deputy chief met President Benjamin Mkapa and
their talks centered on economic adjustments programs in the
country.
</P>
<P>
He will leave here the day after tomorrow. 
</P>
</TEXT>
