<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Balcony Collapse Kills One, Injurying 20 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 18 (Xinhua) -- A second-floor balcony filled
with people seeking a good view of graduation ceremonies of the
University of Virginia in Charlottesville collapsed on Sunday,
killing one person and injuring about 20.
</P>
<P>
The balcony of a faculty residence building gave way about 15
minutes before the commencement was scheduled to begin at 10 a.m.
on the university's central lawn.
</P>
<P>
Those on the balcony fell about 20 feet to the ground, the
Associated Press quoted university spokeswoman Kirsten Katzenbach
as saying.
</P>
<P>
Many of the injured were standing on a walkway beneath the
balcony, a University official said.
</P>
<P>
Twenty people were treated at the University of Virginia
Medical Center. One person died during emergency surgery. A second
person was in critical condition and required surgery.
</P>
<P>
None of the injured were graduates, and commencement continued
as scheduled.
</P>
<P>
Balconies of all the other buildings facing the lawn were
immediately cleared. The university also ordered a safety review
of all the remaining balconies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
