<DOCNO> XIE19970519.0234 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-18 19:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Wishes Speedy End of Zairian Confrontation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 18 (Xinhua) -- Egypt expressed the hope today that
armed confrontation in Zaire will end following recent transfer of
power in the African Great Lake country, the Egyptian MENA news
agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that armed conflicts will come to an end after a
speedy entry of forces of the Alliance of the Democratic Forces
for the Liberations of Congo into Kinshasa and the proclamation of
a new government," a Egyptian foreign ministry official was quoted
by MENA as saying.
</P>
<P>
"Its people have made strongest efforts to realize the
aspirations of African peoples for progress and prosperity," he said.
</P>
<P>
The source also referred to Zaire as the Democratic Republic of
Congo, the name Zairian rebels said they will return the country
to as it first achieved independence in 1960.
</P>
<P>
Rebel leader Laurent Kabila claimed victory Saturday in his
lightning assault across Zaire, while his fighters swept through
Kinshasa, the capital, virtually unopposed by government troops.
</P>
<P>
Kabila promised to name a transitional government within three
days and introduce a new constitution in 60 days. He has declared
himself president, but he set no date for elections.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Zairian Embassy in Cairo has maintained an
attitude of silence and caution as regards the latest developments
in the country where more than 250 ethnic groups live together.
</P>
<P>
The ten diplomats and administrators at the embassy, under the
charge d'affaires, today declined to comment on developments after
Kabila assumed power in Zaire.
</P>
<P>
The security forces guarding the embassy in Zamalek, a plush
living quarter in downtown Cairo, have not been strengthened.
</P>
<P>
Contacted by telephone, the Zairian charge d'affaires told MENA
that the embassy was "working normally" and would maintain its
function pending fresh instructions from the foreign ministry in
Kinshasa.
</P>
<P>
There are in Egypt more than 300 Zairian citizens including
those who were opposed to the deposed President Mobutu Sese Seko.
</P>
<P>
Aides to Mobutu, who relinquished power Friday, either fled or
died at the hands of soldiers in Kinshasa, putting an end to a
nearly 32-year rule of Mobutu in the country of nearly 50 million
people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970519.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-18 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Asks Iran to Prevent PKK Rebels from </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, May 18 (Xinhua) -- Turkey today asked neighboring Iran
to prevent the rebels of the illegal Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK)
from sheltering in the country following the five-day Turkish
cross-border military operation in northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The semi-official Anatolia News Agency this evening quoted
Foreign Ministry spokesman Omer Akbel as saying that the ministry
today summoned the Iranian charge d'affaires in Ankara and told
him that PKK militants, who escaped from their destroyed bases and
camps in northern Iraq, have fled to Iran to seek shelter.
</P>
<P>
"We reaffirmed our request for preventing the PKK rebels
(from fleeing to Iran)," said Akbel.
</P>
<P>
He said that Turkey expected the Iranian security forces to
take preventive measures.
</P>
<P>
Many of the PKK guerrillas are fleeing toward the Iranian
border after being hit hard by Turkish security forces.
</P>
<P>
The agency also quoted sources from Turkey's General Staff as
saying that until 18:30 local time (15:30 GMT) today, the
Turkish government troops had killed 998 PKK rebels during the
Turkish military campaign, which was launched Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Heavy fighting is still continuing in northern Iraq, as the
Turkish government troops are stepping up attack on the PKK rebels
based in the region.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish military operation was launched to support the
Iraqi Kurdistan Democratic Party (KDP), led by Massoud Barzani
who had conducted his own operation against the PKK just hours
before the Turkish incursion.
</P>
<P>
Military sources said that the operation in northern Iraq would
continue until the area was swept free of PKK, which has been
fighting a near 13-year-old separatist war for autonomy in eastern
and southeastern Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970519.0236 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece Considers Changing System for President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, May 18 (Xinhua) -- Greece is now seeking simplification
in election system for the country's head of state.
</P>
<P>
The local newspaper To Vima (The Tribune) reported today, the
Simitis-led government proposed that the Greek constitution be
changed in order to enable the parliament to elect the head of
state by "simple majority without first being obliged to dissolve
and proclaim elections."
</P>
<P>
Under the current election system, which was introduced with
the new constitution in 1975, the president of Greece will be
elected only after three sessions are conducted in the parliament.
In the first two, a two-thirds majority or 200 votes is required
while in the third session the threshold is 180 votes.
</P>
<P>
If no candidate gathers the required number of votes, the
parliament will be dissolved and elections be proclaimed.
</P>
<P>
The resulting parliament requires a simple majority in the
first two votes, and a relative majority in the third to elect a
president. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970519.0237 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Results of Cameroun's Parliamentary ELections to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDE, May 15 (Xinhua) -- Results of the parliamentary
elections in Cameroun will be made public in 20 days, according
to local radio reports today.
</P>
<P>
About 3.5 million Camerounians voted Saturday in 16010 polling
stations nationwide to elect parliamentarians for the 180 seats
in Cameroun's National Assembly.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a presidential decree ordered the re-run today at
the polling in the Diamare rural constituency in the Far-North
Province where voting did not take place due to late arrival of
the election materials.
</P>
<P>
Various divisional supervisional commissions are still to
finish gathering results from far polling stations.
</P>
<P>
According to the law, the election results have to be declared
officially by the constitutional council whose role will be
performed by Cameroun's supreme court which needs up to 20 days
to do the work. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
