</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a presidential decree ordered the re-run today at
the polling in the Diamare rural constituency in the Far-North
Province where voting did not take place due to late arrival of
the election materials.
</P>
<P>
Various divisional supervisional commissions are still to
finish gathering results from far polling stations.
</P>
<P>
According to the law, the election results have to be declared
officially by the constitutional council whose role will be
performed by Cameroun's supreme court which needs up to 20 days
to do the work. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970519.0239 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-05-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uneasy Calm Back to Kinshasa With Social Order </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(by Guo Ming)
</P>
<P>
BRAZZAVILLE, May 18 (Xinhua) -- Zaire's capital Kinshasa was
drawn back to uneasy calm as Laurent Kabila's forces grabbed
control of more areas, but social stability is a far away scene
since quite a number of former government troops went underground
with their guns.
</P>
<P>
Informed sources from the French embassy in Kinshasa said over
200 defeated government troops, whose demand to join Kabila's
forces was initially rejected, attempted to gather at a military
camp to form a military group to be better positioned in talks
with Kabila.
</P>
<P>
"They were members of the presidential guards" loyal to exiled
president Mobutu Sese Seko who had flew to Morocco as a
transition to an uncertain European destination, according to a
diplomat.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, many other soldiers from Zaire's former
regular army, the civilian guards as well as members of the
presidential guards, took to looting and other forms of crime and
offenses, causing concern over the future social stability in the
Zairean capital.
</P>
<P>
Worse, Kinshasa civilians, especially the frustrated youth who
had been struggling to get rid of poverty, also took part in the
large-scale looting on Saturday night, the first day of military
take-over by Kabila's troops.
</P>
<P>
"In Kinshasa you have so many rich people, and so many poor
people at the same time. Some people who took to the street to
loot just think there shouldn't be such a big difference," said a
resident in Kinshasa.
</P>
<P>
"That means Kabila has a lot of things to do," said a Zaire
observer.
</P>
<P>
Kabila, who has proclaimed himself president of the Democratic
Republic of Congo, will have to maintain the social order in the
country, not to say the devastated economy left over by the
Mobutu administration widely accused of corruption and
mismanagement.
</P>
<P>
Following the wide-scale looting last night, Kabila sent his
second dispatch of 900 troops to boost the control of Kinshasa,
raising the total number of "Kabila men in Kinshasa" to about
1,500.
</P>
<P>
"It is not easy to take good care of a newly-captured capital
of five million population with just 1,500 soldiers," said a
British officer based in the Congolese capital of Brazzaville,
opposite to Kinshasa just across the Zaire River.
</P>
<P>
The troops of the Alliance of Democratic Forces for the
Liberation of Congo-Zaire (ADFL) have so far controlled all the
major military camps, the state radio and television stations,
the Presidential Palace, the prime minister's office, the
parliament, the post office, among other key buildings in
Kinshasa.
</P>
<P>
"But vast areas of the capital are far away from actual
control," said a United States military officer in Brazzaville.
</P>
<P>
Zaire's state tv and radio, already controlled by Kabila's
forces, today repeatedly broadcast an order from Kabila, saying
that any forms of crime including looting are strictly forbidden,
and looters would be severely punished.
</P>
<P>
Kabila also called on local residents in Kinshasa to remain
calm and carry on their normal business.
</P>
<P>
But observers said it really takes time for peace and
stability dawns upon Kinshasa, capital of Africa's third largest
country taken over in an amazing speed by Kabila's forces since
their uprising in October 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
